5. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 643565965
T1  - AMYOTROPHIC LATERAL SCLEROSIS - A RARE PRESENTATION
T3  - 18th Conference in Internal Medicine. Lisbon Portugal.
A1  - Maia R.
A1  - Moreira M.
A1  - Silva D.
A1  - Pinto P.
A1  - Costa M.
A1  - Torre E.
A1  - Rodrigues C.
A1  - Guerra D. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Introduction Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS) is an incurable and progressive neurodegenerative disease, with an annual incidence of 1-3/100,000 cases. It is characterized by the presence of signs and symptoms of first and second motor neurons, simultaneously. Case description Female, 72 years old, hypertensive, diabetic, with dyslipidaemia, non-smoker, autonomous, admitted to the Emergency Department due to worsening of the general state, gait slowing and dyspnoea. Asthenia, anorexia and weight loss (33 lbs) in 10 months. After undergoing Holter-24h, electromyography (EMG), echocardiogram, endoscopic study, bone scintigraphy and abdominal ultrasound, with unremarkable results, her family doctor made a diagnosis of Depression. At the physic examination: conscious, cooperative and oriented, with slowed speech, mucocutaneous pallor, blood pressure 185/74 mmHg, oxygen saturation (SatO2) 86% (FiO2 21%). Cardiac Auscultation (A): S1 and S2 present, rhythmic, grade III/VI systolic murmur. Pulmonary A: respiratory sounds diminished, increased expiratory time. Gasometry (FiO2 21%), global respiratory insufficiency (RI): pH 7.35, pCO2 71 mmHg, pO2 51 mmHg, HCO3 40 mmol/L, SatO2 88%. Admitted to the Internal Medicine Service for hospitalization. Abdominopelvic CT - adenoma of the right adrenal gland. Mycobacteria cultural exam - negative. Despite normal ambulatory exams results, repeated EMG revealed a motor neuron disease, with bulbar attainment. Due to worsening IR, with acidaemia, non-invasive ventilation was started. The patient was later evaluated by Neurology and Pneumology that corroborated the diagnostic hypothesis placed - ALS. Follow-up: Progressive worsening of clinical condition, having died two months later. Discussion The authors intend to highlight the atypical presentation of the disease and the inclusion of this type of pathologies in the differential diagnosis of RI. RI is a life threatening symptom and is the most common cause of death in these patients. It may be the first manifestation of the disease, but it occurs more often months or years after the remaining symptomatology.
