30. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 630933710
T1  - Physiopathology, Diagnosis, and Treatment of Functional Pituitary Dysfunction
T2  - Endocrinology (Switzerland)
A1  - Miljic D.
A1  - Pekic S.
A1  - Stojanovic M.
A1  - Popovic V. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Neuroendocrine signals are integrated by the hypothalamus. Both hypothalamic and peripheral hormone signals are executed in the pituitary. Functional hypothalamic-pituitary changes may develop as a result of chronic stress, energy imbalance (both positive-obesity and negative-anorexia nervosa), and critical illness. Abnormalities of the endocrine system include increased activity of hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis (HPA), impaired growth hormone axis, gonadal and thyroid dysfunction, and alteration in prolactin secretion. These hormonal alterations may also contribute to the development of underlying condition. A skillful use of dynamic tests together with careful clinical evaluation and follow-up are necessary to establish the correct diagnosis. Some of these changes are viewed as adaptive, and improvement in pituitary dysfunctions is expected with reversal of causation.Copyright © 2018, Springer International Publishing AG, part of Springer Nature.
