A1  - De Laffolie J. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Objectives and Study: Methylmalonic acidemia (MMA) and propionic acidemia (PA) are very rare autosomal-recessive inherited metabolic diseases from the group of organoacidopathies. Katabolism due to minor infections can lead to metabolic decompensation including hyperammonemia and ketoacidosis, especially in small children. We present data from a small cohort to clarify whether placement of a percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy with jejunal tube (PEG-J) reduce metabolic imbalances and hospital stays. Method(s): 4 patients with MMA (N=3) or PA (N=1) were included. Data were collected at every investigation, in particular pH value, pCO2, bicarbonate, base excess, ammonia and lactate. Due to repeated metabolic derailments, a percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy was placed for postpyloric nutrition. Result(s): In patient 1, maximum of ammonia level before placement of PEG was 310 mu mol/l (median 94, IQR: 82-154) with a median base excess of-8.3 (IQR:-12.7-4.6), after placement of PEG maximum of ammonia level was 137 mu mol/l (median 73, IQR: 43-114) and median base excess was 8.55 (IQR:-11.225-5.875). The number of hospital stays was reduced from 3.0 per year with a median of treatment days of 4.5 (IQR: 3.75-13.25) to a number of hospital days of 0.92 per year with a median of treatment days of 8 (IQR: 6.5-9.5). This effect was also evident in patient 2. Maximum of ammonia level before placement of PEG was 328 mu mol/l (median 103,5, IQR: 92-124), median of base excess was-13.4 (IQR-16.15-5.15), after placement of PEG maximum of ammonia level was 72 mu mol/l (median 68, IQR: 66-70) and median of base excess was-0.35 (IQR:-2.25-0.05), hospital stays was reduced too (1.89 hospital stays per year with a median of 8 treatment days (IQR: 3.75-14), compared to 1.39 hospital stays per year after placement of PEG with a median of treatment days of 5 (IQR: 0)). This effect was also evident in patient 3 (maximum of ammonia level before placement of PEG 371 mu mol/l (median 109,5, IQR: 87.75-119.25) with a median base excess of-5.8 (IQR:-15-5.3), after placement of PEG maximum of ammonia level was 135 mu mol/l (median 73,5, IQR: 62.25-93.5) and median of base excess was-9.2 (IQR:-11.7-5.6)). The number of metabolic derailments and subsequent hospital stays did not decrease, however the number of treatment days (3.13 hospital stays per year with a median of treatment days of 9 (IQR 8-12.25), to 3.26 hospital stays per year with a median of treatment days of 7 (IQR: 5-9)). Patient 3 developed a chronic kidney failure as a result of MAA, which also increased the number of hospitalizations. A metabolic transplant is currently being prepared. Our currently youngest patient stayed in hospital for 7 times with a median of treatment days of 8 (IQR: 5.25-14.5) until age of 11 months. The maximum of ammonia level in this period was 975 mu mol/l (median 98, IQR: 73.25-158) with a median base excess of-29.2 (IQR: 0). Conclusion(s): Placement of a percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy with postpyloric tube appears to reduce the rate of metabolic decompensations. In addition, hospital stays and especially the number of treatment days can be reduced. This method, especially the placement of a postpyloric tube could enable parents to prevent catabolism when vomiting begins by continuously feeding through the jejunal thigh.
