98. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2018725375
T1  - 006 Lifestyle intervention in PCOS
T3  - EBCOG 2021. Athens Greece.
A1  - Piltonen T. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Adolescent with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) are at high risk for obesity and metabolic derangements and the weight trajectory seems to deviate very early on before the age of 5. This early rise in BMI (early adiposity rebound) has been shown to be a risk factor for adverse metabolic outcomes later in life in general population. Also, the weight gain from adolescence to adulthood seems to be more rapid in PCOS and the prevalence of PCOS seems to increase along increasing BMI. Also, in PCOS adolescents, high weight and abdominal obesity are risk factors for type 2 diabetes and metabolic syndrome. As recommended by the international evidence based PCOS guideline, lifestyle modification should be the first line treatment for all women diagnosed with the syndrome. Due to limited data on PCOS adolescents, many of the recommendations bases on the data on general population or in adults. According to previous literature lifestyle intervention, preferably with multidisciplinary approach, is efficient to improve PCOS symptoms and reduce weight in adolescents. Only 5-10% weight reduction seems to improve PCOS symptoms. The diet recommendation does not promote specific diet. Around 30% calory deficiency per day is sufficient in adults to reduce weight. Some studies also show this being efficient in adolescents, although the diet advice should focus more on altering the food items rather than eating less. Exercise 60 min/day 3 times a week is also recommend as well as avoidance of sedentary behavior. All approaches should be patient centered and take also into consideration the psychological, and cultural aspects. As PCOS is a risk factor for mental distress and disordered eating, lifestyle advice for an adolescent should be carried out supervised. Metformin can be added to the lifestyle intervention in overweight or obese adolescents, after discussing through the possible side effect profile that could reduce adherence to this therapy. It should be noted that some countries may not have approval to use metformin in adolescents. Also combined contraceptives together with lifestyle therapy may have positive synergistic effect on weight reduction. All in all, more lifestyle intervention studies with longer follow-up should be carried out to improve tools and practices especially for adolescents.Copyright © 2022
