N2  - Objectives Anorexia nervosa (AN) and polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) are both associated with oligo-/amenorrhea and low estrogen, a crucial hormone for bone mineral accrual. The primary goal of this study was to compare subtotal whole body (STWB) BMD and lumbar spine (LS) BMD by DXA in adolescents and young adults with AN and PCOS and age -and BMI- comparable controls. We hypothesized that BMD would be stratified by relative estrogen status with AN lowest, PCOS intermediate, and controls highest. We expected that LSBMD, comprising primarily trabecular or hormonally sensitive bone, would be affected more than STWBBMD. A secondary goal was to investigate the effect of percentage body fat (%BF) on BMD among the groups. We hypothesized that %BF would be protective of BMD. Methods This was a retrospective study of a convenience sample of 26 female adolescents and young adults (ages 15 - 25 years old; mean=18;median=17), (AN: n =9; PCOS n=9; Controls n=8), (%BF: AN =29; PCOS =34.5; Controls =31.3) from the Columbia University Irving Medical Center Pediatric DXA Database. A 4500W Discovery Model Hologic DXA Scanner with APEX software was used. The pediatric z-score calculator of the Research Institute at the Children's Hospital of Philadelphia was used to calculate BMD z-scores both unadjusted and adjusted for height. We used a one-way ANOVA to assess the effects of AN, PCOS, and controls on STWBBMD and LSBMD with SAS software 13.1, SAS Institute Cary North Carolina. Results AN had lower LSBMD (0.871 +/- 0.039 g/cm2;z-score = -0.9 +/- 0.4) compared to PCOS (1.041 +/- 0.039 g/cm2;z-score = 0.7 +/- 0.4 ) (p < 0.02 ); however, LSBMD was not different from controls (0.980 +/- 0.04 g/cm2;z-score 0.2 +/- 0.4) in AN or PCOS. The difference in LSBMD did not remain significant when adjusted for %BF. Additionally, there was no difference among the 3 groups in STWBBMD. Conclusions In this study LSBMD was lower in AN than in PCOS, but neither study group differed from the control group. When adjusted for %BF, the observed difference in LSBMD between AN and PCOS was no longer significant. We did not see the anticipated stratified effect on LSBMD, perhaps due to the protective androgen effect on bone in PCOS. Our findings emphasize the importance of detecting and treating low BMD, specifically in AN, who in this study have BMD close to 1 standard deviation below the mean. Future larger studies will be instrumental in attaining a better understanding of bone health in adolescents and young adults with AN and PCOS.
