157. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2011987202
T1  - GUT MICROBIOME SAMPLES-DOES STOOL REPRESENT RIGHT?
T3  - DDW 2021. Virtual, Online.
A1  - Levitan O.
A1  - Burleson D.B.
A1  - McCaffrey P.
A1  - Ma L.
A1  - Vala A.
A1  - Johnson D.A. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Introduction Numerous studies discuss the gut microbiome; however, they are mainly basedon stool samples obtained at home by spontaneous passage. We hypothesized that theyserve as a poor proxy for understanding the more proximal colonic microbiome. To addressthis hypothesis. we studied data from metagenomic sequencing of stool samples versus moreproximal, inner-colonic effluent samples collected during high-volume water irrigation bowelpreparation (BP). Methods Samples were collected prospectively from 20 participants duringtwo IRB-approved clinical trials. All patients underwent an FDA-cleared high-volume colonirrigation (Hygieacare, Norfolk VA) before screening colonoscopy. The inner colonic samples(n=62) were collected three times during the BP to represent the left, transverse, and rightcolon. Stool samples were collected by patients in their homes (n=20) using a standardizedkit. Metagenomic sequencing was done using NovaSeq 6000 (40M short reads, SeqMatic,Freemont CA). Taxonomic classification of the 150-base-pair paired-end reads was performedby Kraken2 and taxonomic analysis was done by R studio (version 4.0.2). Biosynthetic geneclusters (BGC) were identified by the VBx1 analysis pipeline (VastBiomeTM, Milbrae CA).Results Patients age was 65+/-10 (min-41, max-78), 60% female (n=12) and 40% male (n=8), with BMI of 28+/-6 (min-19, max-43). Bacterial communities detected in inner colonicsamples were significantly different than those of stool samples. There was a clear biogeographygradient of bacteria along the colon, where the alpha diversity by Shannon index ineach sample type decreased towards the small intestine. Principal Coordinates Analysis(PCoA) with Bray-Curtis dissimilarity matrix distances revealed significant phylogeneticdifferences between the stool and inner-colonic samples. The differential abundance ofspecies between the sample types shows a 5-fold increase in the right colon. The BGCanalysis reveals a presence of BGCs found only in the different colon segments. Altogether69% of the BGCs detected in the study were unique to the inner-colonic samples. ConclusionsThere are distinctive and large differences between the microbiome of stool and the moreproximal, inner-colonic samples. The high percentage of the inner-colonic unique BGCsrepresents the extent for multiple biosynthetic processes, found only in those samples. Thepatented collection of microbial samples using high-volume colon irrigation is currently theonly way of non-invasively obtaining microbiome information from within the colon andwithout the effects of oral prep purgatives. The significant differences detected in this studyand the unique contribution of the more proximal colonic samples to the microbiota suggeststhat information from these samples is imperative for developing future biomarkers, targetedtherapeutics, and personalized medicine.(Figure Presented)Figure 1 - Phylogenetic diversity between stool and the three colon effluent samples. A.Alpha diversity by the Shannon index; B. Principal Coordinates Analysis (PCoA) using Bray-Curtis dissimilarity matrix. Number of samples - stool samples - n=20, Effluent-1 - n=24,Effluent-2 - n=22, Effluent-3 n=22. Statistical significance- the p value-cut off: ns-p > 0.05;* - p 0.05; **- p  0.01; ***- p  0.001; ****- p 0.0001(Figure Presented) Figure 2-Biosynthetic gene clusters (BGCs) analysis of stool and colon effluent samples.On the left - a Venn diagram of stool versus all the BGCs from three types of effluentsamples combined. On the right - number (and percentage) of unique BGCs identified inthe different colon effluent samples. Number of samples - stool samples - n=20, Effluent-1 - n=22, Effluent-2 - n=20, Effluent-3 n=20.Copyright © 2021 AGA Institute
