159. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 636560648
T1  - Analysis of the differences between two methods for the determination of sex hormone-binding globulin (SHBG)
T3  - 24th IFCC-EFLM European Congress of Clinical Chemistry and Laboratory Medicine, EUROMEDLAB 2021. Munich.
A1  - Gorrin Ramos J.
A1  - Morante Palacios M.C. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - BACKGROUND-AIM Sex hormone-binding globulin (SHBG) is a glycoprotein that fixes sex hormones, mainly dihydrotestosterone, testosterone and estradiol. The bioavailability of these hormones is influenced by the concentration of SHBG which can be altered by various clinical situations. Polycystic ovary syndrome, diabetes or hypothyroidism lead to decreased levels of SHBG while pregnancy, hyperthyroidism or anorexia increases concentration. It correlates negatively with the inflammatory state of the organism. The objective of this study is to assess the differences between two methods of quantitative analysis of SHBG. METHODS A total of 69 patient samples were included, 55% women and 45% men (15-56 years). Measurement range = 10-110 nmol/L. The new method (Chemiluminescence, in Maglumi 1000, SNIBE) was compared against the reference method (Microparticle chemiluminescence, in Alinity i, Abbott). Method comparison analysis was performed using SPSS v21.0. A regression analysis was performed between the results obtained by both methods and the difference between them was studied using a Bland-Altman analysis. RESULTS Both techniques show a good degree of correlation (r=0.97). The resulting equation, y= 1.055x-0.0052. Bland-Altman analysis shows a mean of difference -3.45 +/- 1.86. CONCLUSIONS Based on the statistical analysis of the data, both techniques present a high degree of correlation between the results. They do not present differences of proportional type or constant type, therefore we can conclude that it is not necessary to modify the reference values provided by the supplier.
