AN  - 2015635758
T1  - Transcutaneous auricular vagal nerve stimulation is a promising therapeutic approach for weight management in females with polycystic ovary syndrome
T3  - 4th International Brain Stimulation Meeting. Charleston United States.
A1  - Ling J.
A1  - Yu Y.
A1  - Zhang M.
A1  - Du X. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Abstract Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is an endocrine disorder characterized by insulin resistance and hyperandrogenism, afflicting females from adolescence to reproductive age with increased rates of overweight, obesity, and higher incidences of type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and endometrial cancer. Calorie restriction and physical activity are major weight loss strategies for most PCOS women. Ovary functions are regulated by the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis and parasympathetic innervation via the vagal nerves, whose fibers project from the nucleus of the solitary tract (NTS) to the hypothalamus. Vagal nerve stimulation (VNS) has been proven to prevent weight gain under a high-fat diet by controlling metabolism and innervating gut movement. As a non-invasive neuromodulation technique, transcutaneous auricular vagal nerve stimulation (taVNS) has shown positive results in diabetes researches included relieving impaired glucose tolerance and ameliorating the depression-like behavior. We have previously found that taVNS attenuates weight gain without decreasing food intake in Zucker diabetic fatty rats and inhibits hypothalamic P2Y1R expression. In consideration of its role in endocrine regulation and neuromodulation, we proposed that taVNS is a promising therapeutic approach for weight management in PCOS women. Funding(s): Youth Project of Beijing Shijitan Hospital (2019-q04); National Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine (2019XZZX-JB004). National Natural Science Foundation of China (82104980). Keywords: transcutaneous auricular vagal nerve stimulation (taVNS), polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), weight managementCopyright © 2021
