161. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 636386835
T1  - Increased prevalence of metabolic risk factors associated with nafld in obese adolescents with pcos
T3  - 72nd Annual Meeting of the American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases, AASLD 2021. Virtual.
A1  - Patel N.
A1  - Perito E.R.
A1  - Tsai P.
A1  - Sarkar M. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Background: Nonalcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) is the most common chronic liver disease in children and adolescents; and can lead to cirrhosis and need for transplant in adulthood. Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) increases NAFLD risk and severity in young adult women, though data on PCOS and NAFLD in adolescents are lacking. Method(s): Cross-sectional study of female adolescents aged 12-18 years old with ICD code for overweight or obesity between 2012-2020, comparing individuals with PCOS, by ICD code, to age-matched controls without PCOS, who had suspected NAFLD. Suspected NAFLD was defined as steatosis on imaging, ALT >= 44 U/L x 2 and/or >=80 U/L x 1, in absence of other chronic liver disease, binge alcohol use (> 8 drinks per week), hormonal therapy for gender reassignment, parenteral nutrition, or use of pro-steatotic medications. Metabolic characteristics were compared including BMI, type 2 diabetes (DM2), prediabetes, dyslipidemia (total cholesterol > 95%ile for age (198mg/dL), LDL > 95%ile (137 mg/dl) or HDL < 5%ile (35 mg/dl)), and triglyceride: HDL-C ratio as a surrogate measure of insulin resistance. Result(s): We identified 24 obese/overweight adolescents with PCOS to have suspected NAFLD, and 17 cases in non-PCOS controls, with median age of 15.2 (IQR 13.7-16.5). ALT levels were numerically higher in adolescents with PCOS vs. non PCOS controls (55 vs. 38, p=0.13). Demographic risk factors for NAFLD such as race/ethnicity and BMI %ile were similar by PCOS status though presence and severity of several metabolic risk factors were greater in adolescents with PCOS, namely dyslipidemia (50.0% vs. 17.6%, p=0.03) and pre-diabetes (33.3% vs. 5.9%, p=0.04). LDL levels were significantly higher (105 vs. 84, p=0.03). Though not statistically significant, hypertension (4.2% vs. 0.0%, p = 0.39), hypertriglyceridemia (66.7% vs. 52.9%, p = 0.38), and DM2 (29.2% vs. 11.8%, p=0.19) were more common and glucose (mg/dL) (107 vs. 95, p=0.08), and triglyceride levels (mg/dL) (179 vs. 142, p=0.40) were greater in patients with PCOS. Conclusion(s): Among overweight/obese female adolescents with suspected NAFLD, metabolic risk factors were more common with PCOS, including dyslipidemia and pre-diabetes. These metabolic derangements may help to explain the early onset of NASH with fibrosis seen in young women with NAFLD and PCOS and highlight the importance of inquiring about PCOS related symptoms in adolescents presenting for pediatric NAFLD care.
