166. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634773252
T1  - Infant with pertussis pneumonia, hyperlymphocytosis, pulmonary hypertension and multi-organ failure treated with two double volume echange transfusions
T3  - 10th World Congress of the World Federation of Pediatric Intensive and Critical Care Societies, WFPICCS 2020. Virtual.
A1  - Bonos P.
A1  - Prezerakou A.
A1  - Patsoura A.
A1  - Vasilopoulou I.
A1  - Nikolaou F. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - AIMS & OBJECTIVES: Aims and Objectives: To highlight the significance of double volume exchange transfusion (DVET) in severe life-threatening pertussis infection. METHOD(S): A 35 days-old infant was admitted to our PICU with a history of rhinitis, poor feeding, progressive respiratory distress, paroxysmal cough inducing apnea and cyanosis. On admission, the patient was hemodynamically stable with mild respiratory distress (45breaths/min, heat rate 175-190 beats/min), without fever. Due to pneumonia on chest radiography, leukocytosis WBC: 54,100/mm3 and positive PCR of nasopharynx specimen for pertussis, she was treated with azithromycin. Ten hours later, because of pneumonia and rapid increase of leukocytosis WBC: 71,000/mm3 (without pulmonary hypertension), she underwent a DVET, after which, WBC decreased to 23,000/mm3. On hospital day 4, she developed progressive respiratory failure, she was intubated and underwent mechanical ventilation. A second DVET was performed due to new WBC elevation (up to 69,300/mm3) and pulmonary hypertension, which was treated with sildenafil. After the second DVET, WBC decreased to 16,400/mm3, however, she developed cardiopulmonary failure (hypotension, acidosis pH: 6,92, persistent hypoxemia and increasing hypercarbia up to PCO2:132mmHg) and she was treated with inotropes and High Frequency Oscillatory ventilation (HFOV). RESULT(S): Gradually, the infant improved and she managed to wean from inotropes a few hours later and from mechanical ventilation after six days. Sixteen days after her admission, she was discharged from the PICU in a satisfactory condition. CONCLUSION(S): The early and repeated (if necessary) treatment of severe pertussis infection with DVETs may decrease the mortality of this disease, especially in young infants.
