167. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634767609
T1  - A hidden issue in plain sight: A case of euglycemic DKA in the setting of pancreatitis
T3  - 50th Critical Care Congress. Virtual.
A1  - Adrianza A.
A1  - Diaz D. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) is a lifethreatening condition characterized by hyperglycemia, metabolic acidosis, and increased serum ketones. Euglycemic DKA, is a less common entity that can go unrecognized due its milder hyperglycemic levels of less than 200 mg/dl at presentation, and result in a delayed diagnosis and treatment. We report a case of eu-DKA precipitated by hypertriglyceridemia pancreatitis, starvation ketosis while on sodium glucose transporter SGLT2 inhibitors. METHOD(S): A 57-year-old female with history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, hyperlipidemia and migraines, presented after 5 days of nausea, vomiting, decreased food intake and worsening sharp abdominal pain, radiating to the back. Her medications included metformin, glimepiride, empagliflozin, fenofibrate, amitriptyline and erenumab. On admission, laboratory results showed a serum glucose of 201 mg/dl, sodium of 133 mmol/L, chloride of 109 and a bicarbonate level of 6 mmol/L, an anion gap of 23, a creatinine of 0.5 mg/dl and a lipase of 5172. Computed tomography revealed findings consistent with pancreatitis. No evidence of cholelithiasis or common bile duct dilation were observed. Aggressive fluid resuscitation was initiated, serum glucose was covered with an insulin sliding scale and pain was managed with hydromorphone. Eighteen hours after intensive fluid resuscitation bicarbonate level remained low at 9 mmol/L and the anion gap remained at 22 mmol/L. Arterial blood gases revealed pH 6.86, pCO2 13 mm Hg. Further work-up revealed ketonuria, large ketonemia, negative lactic acid, negative blood alcohol level, and a triglyceride level of 2407 mg/dL. She was admitted to the intensive care unit. Insulin drip and IV fluid resuscitation with dextrose was initiated. Her clinical status improved, and hypoglycemic medications were optimized. RESULT(S): This scenario among severe hypertriglyceridemia pancreatitis, ketoacidosis, and starvation emphasizes the fact that euglycemic DKA should be considered in the differential diagnosis of an ill patient presenting with metabolic acidosis. The increase use of SGLT2 inhibitors should make clinicians more aware of such scenarios. Ketoacidosis, even in the absence of marked hyperglycemia, remains a life-threatening disease that needs a prompt diagnosis and management.
