214. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634461730
T1  - Medical and surgical management of weight loss
T3  - Annual Meeting of the North American Menopause Society, NAMS 2020. Virtual.
A1  - Bessesen D.H. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Obesity is common, growing in incidence and is associated with some of the most common health problems seen in adults including type 2 diabetes, coronary artery disease, obstructive sleep apnea, infertility, a variety of cancers (including breast, ovarian and endometrial), degenerative joint disease, depression and disability to name just a few. Changes in diet/physical activity, weight loss medications and bariatric surgery are the treatment options currently available to patients with obesity. It is important for health care providers to be comfortable discussing weight and weight loss treatments with their patients. Remembering that ultimately, responsibility for decisions about obesity treatment rests with the patient with support and information from the care provider can help the provider engage in a non-judgmental, supportive conversation about weight. Any weight loss treatment chosen will only work as long as the person adheres to it and providers should emphasize the need for long-term treatment for this chronic, often progressive disease. The appropriate treatment approach for an individual person depends on their degree of excess weight and the presence of associated health problems. Treatments that are more aggressive are appropriate for those individuals more severely affected by obesity. Lifestyle changes produce on average 5-10% weight loss. There is no one dietary strategy that has been shown to be best for weight loss. The best dietary approach is the one that the person can adhere to. Recent studies of intermittent fasting and time restricted feeding show promise as alternatives to macronutrient or calorie based approach. Commercial programs are another option that busy clinicians can feel comfortable recommending. Exercise appears to be important for weight loss maintenance but produces only about 2% weight loss when used as a primary weight loss strategy. Orlistat, phentermine, the combinations of phentermine/topiramate or bupropion/naltrexone and liraglutide 3 mg are currently available FDA approved weight loss medications. A number of new agents are under active investigation. These medications give 5-10% more weight loss than lifestyle treatments alone. Sleeve gastrectomy and gastric bypass surgery give 22-30% weight loss and have dramatic benefits on weight related co-morbidities, especially type 2 diabetes. While the numbers given above reflect the average weight loss seen with each category of treatment, dramatic inter-individual differences in actual weight loss are characteristic of each approach. Weight loss has beneficial effects on women's reproductive function and fertility although there are some specific concerns related to pregnancy following bariatric surgery. An appreciation of the basic principles of common counseling theories including the transtheoretical model, the health belief model, motivational interviewing, values based counseling and cognitive behavior therapy, can help even busy clinicians have more productive and rewarding conversations with their patients about weight.
