217. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634134225
T1  - Euglycaemic ketoacidosis during continuous renal replacement therapy
T3  - 4th Asia Pacific AKI CRRT Congress 2020. Bangkok Thailand.
A1  - Ting S.
A1  - Cove M.E.
A1  - Chua H.-R. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Background: Continuous renal replacement therapy (CRRT) is the preferred modality of dialysis in haemodynamically unstable patients. Commercially available CRRT solutions do not always contain glucose. Method(s): We describe a patient who developed worsening acidosis during CRRT in the ICU. Local ethics board waived informed consent (NHG-DSRB-2016/01243). Result(s): A 76-year-old man admitted for septic shock secondary to pneumonia, was initiated on CRRT for acute kidney injury and metabolic acidosis (pH 7.11, pCO2 40 mmHg, bicarbonate 12.3 mmol/L, lactate 7.1 mmol/L, creatinine 231 mu mol/L). The mode used was CVVHD, and the replacement solution was glucose-free PrismaSol (Baxter International, USA). Acidosis improved (pH 7.30, pCO2 33 mmHg, bicarbonate 16.8 mmol/L, creatinine 172 mu mol/L), but did not resolve despite lactate normalising (2.1 mmol/L). The anion gap remained elevated (27 mmol/L). During investigation of the high anion gap acidosis, serum betahydroxybutyrate was found to be elevated (5.2 mmol/L), leading to a diagnosis of euglycaemic ketoacidosis. The patient had type 2 diabetes (HbA1c 8.4%), treated with oral medications, but was not taking a sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT-2) inhibitor. CRRT had normalised serum glucose and the patient's insulin infusion had been stopped. The acidosis rapidly resolved after commencing insulin (4 units/hour), and increasing caloric intake (19 to 26 kcal/kg/day) by starting a dextrose infusion. Conclusion(s): Ketoacidosis occurs in the setting of insulin deficiency, and patients with type 2 diabetes have relative insulin deficiency. Dialysis with CRRT using glucose-free solutions may lead to normoglycaemia with minimal or no insulin, because up to 80 g/day of glucose is lost in the effluent, and enteral feeding frequently does not meet caloric goals in early critical illness. This highlights that CRRT can induce euglycaemic ketoacidosis, and is easily treated by maintaining an insulin and dextrose infusion, or prevented by adding glucose to CRRT solutions.
