218. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 633719381
T1  - HMG (3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl) CoA-lyase deficiency and T2D with insulin resistance (IR) and PCOS
T3  - 2020 American Association of Clinical Endocrinologists Annual Scientific and Clinical Congress, AACE 2020. Washington DC United States.
A1  - Aijaz W.
A1  - Ahsan T.A.
A1  - Ghaus S. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Introduction: A case of neonatal hypoglycemia secondary to HMG CoA-lyase deficiency and T2D with insulin resistance (IR) and PCOS Case Description: Female, 21 years, presented with progressive weight gain, irregular menses and mild facial hirsutism for 1 year. She had been diagnosed with HMG-CoA lyase deficiency after having hypoglycemic fits since birth; was advised 2 hourly feeding with protein restricted diet. She experienced frequent episodes of hypoglycemia till the age of 5 years and had been overweight since childhood. Her younger brother also had HMG-CoA lyase deficiency. She was an offspring of consanguineous marriage and her parents and grandparents had T2D. Her BMI was 35.8 kg/m2, marked acanthosis nigricans, mild facial hair on chin. Her fasting blood sugar was 142 mg/dl, HbA1C of 7.5% and fasting insulin levels of 25.5 uIu/ml. Ultrasound pelvis showed dense ovarian stroma with no follicles. Discussion(s): HMG-CoA lyase deficiency is a rare (<1/100,000 live neonates) autosomal recessive disorder caused by mutation in HMGCL gene. It is a mitochondrial enzyme that catalyzes the HMG-CoA to acetyl CoA and acetoacetate, common final step of ketogenesis and leucine metabolism, which then leads to accumulation of HMG-CoA, inhibiting gluconeogenesis and urea cycle, promoting hypoglycemia and hyperammonemia. In view of the strong family history of T2D and cutaneous marker of IR, it is likely that she has T2D as well, even though the possibility of another genetic disorder, like MODY has not been ruled out. The disorder of HMG-CoA lyase deficiency itself doesn't explain the development of diabetes, however, repeated intake of food to avoid hypoglycemia may have led to the obesity, thus unmasking the familial predisposition to T2D. To the best of our knowledge there is no reported case of diabetes and IR reported so far with HMG-CoA lyase deficiency.
