221. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2005421128
T1  - 4. Ovarian Reserve in Adolescents and Young Adults with Anorexia Nervosa
T3  - NASPAG 34th Annual Clinical Research Meeting. Houston United States.
A1  - Pitts S.
A1  - Gallagher J.S.
A1  - Gordon C.
A1  - DiVasta A. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Background: Hypothalamic amenorrhea is common in adolescents and young adults (AYAs) with anorexia nervosa (AN), and ovarian reserve is not routinely assessed as part of routine clinical care. Multiple neuroendocrine alterations occur with AN, and appear to impair reproductive health. AN leads to higher rates of fertility problems, later age at childbearing, and increased rates of obstetrical complications. How or when AN negatively influences future fertility is unclear. We sought to determine whether biomarkers of ovarian reserve were impacted in AYA with AN. Method(s): We measured serum anti-Mullerian hormone (AMH) and inhibin B ) levels in 97 female subjects with AN and amenorrhea at the baseline visit of a clinical trial, prior to intervention, and in 20 age-matched controls without aneating disorder or known menstrual dysfunction. Wilcoxon ranked-sum testing compared demographic characteristics and hormone concentrations between groups, while linear regression (a priori adjusted for age and BMI) was used to determine factors associated with AMH and inhibin B. Statistical analyses were performed using SAS v.9.3. This study was approved by our local IRB. Result(s): Subjects with AN reported amenorrhea for 6 months on average, and had a percentage median BMI for age that was much lower than controls (Table 1). AMH levels were higher in participants with AN than controls (4.7 +/- 3.2 vs. 3.2 +/- 3.0 ng/mL; p=0.02). Subjects with AN had an AMH level 2.03 ng/mL higher than a control subject (Table 2), but little of the variability in AMH between subjects with AN and controls was explained by our regression model (r2=0.08). Neither FSH nor inhibin B differed between AN and controls. In 19.6% of participants with AN, AMH levels were elevated above the normal range. Among the subjects with AN, those with high AMH had a longer duration of disease than those with normal AMH levels (26.4 +/- 30.1 vs. 9.8 +/- 17.9 mos; p=0.02); age or degree of malnutrition did not differ between AN subjects with normal or elevated AMH. Conclusion(s): Ovarian reserve was not negatively impacted in AYA with AN. In fact, AMH levels were elevated in AYA with AN compared to healthy controls. Almost 1/5 of participants with AN demonstrated an elevated AMH level, as is seen in polycystic ovary syndrome. A low AMH in patients with AN should raise clinical concern, and should not be attributed to degree of malnutrition alone. Potential links between the hypothalamic amenorrhea suffered by patients with AN and PCOS should be explored. Support: NICHD 5K23HD060066 LEAH training grant T71MC00009, MCHB, HRSA. [Formula presented] [Formula presented]Copyright © 2020
