AN  - 2005256486
T1  - SUN-069 Disequilibrium Syndrome In Intermittent Hemodialysis Setting: A Case Report And Review Of Literature
T3  - ISN World Congress of Nephrology. Abu Dhabi United Arab Emirates.
A1  - akl A.
A1  - OSAILAN A.
A1  - farugui H. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Introduction: Dialysis disequilibrium syndrome, firstly described in 1962 [1], is well-known complication during hemodialysis, which characterizes as nausea, vomiting, headache, visual acuity disturbance, tremor, muscle twisting, disorientation, confusion, seizure or even coma [2,3]. Several predisposing factors have been described to be associated with DDS, including the first hemodialysis, severe uremia, age, pre-existing neurological disorders, and metabolic acidosis [4]. 51-year old male with no previous medical history, two months ago found to have obstructive acute kidney failure due to bilateral ureteric stones and was admitted to other hospital. Urgent hemodialysis was done followed by bilateral stone removal and insertion of double J stents. However, his renal function did not improve after the procedure and they declared him having advanced stage of CKD. The patient presented to our hospital complaining of generalized fatigue and anorexia in the last 3 days. Laboratory investigation showed a PH 7,36, PCO2 26,2, HCO3 14,5, serum creatinine 9.69 mg/dl, Urea 111 mg/dl, Serum potassium 3.6mmol/l, serum sodium 108 mmol/l. The patient found to have asymptomatic hyponatremia with no indication for urgent hemodialysis. Diagnostic imaging demonstrates Bilateral renal double J stent with both kidneys demonstrate increased in cortical echogenicity and mild-to-moderate hydronephrosis. The patient started on intravenous hypertonic saline 10 meq/hr for 4 hours to reach the target of serum sodium from 115 to 120mmol/l in the first 24 hours to avoid rapid correction with serum sodium monitoring every 6 hours. Serum sodium reached 115 mmol/l in the first 24 hours, then later it was 119 mmol/l in the second day. At this level of serum sodium 119 mmol/l the patient started to complain of uremic manifestations with fluid overload and a hemodialysis session was prescribed. Repeated Laboratory investigations showed PH 7,4, PCO2 37,9, HCO3 27,1, serum creatinine 4.66 mg/dl, Urea 48,22 mg/dl, Serum potassium 3.0 mmol/l and serum sodium 133 mmol/l, daily serum sodium and BUN levels are shown in Figure 1. In the early morning of day 3 after the hemodialysis, the patient developed acute weakness in both extremities with slurred speech, followed by decrease of his level of consciousness. Later in the same day, the patient transferred to intensive care unit because of the marked changes of his conscious level. In the intensive care unit, patient had one attack of seizure which was evaluated by neurologist as a case of metabolic encephalopathy vs central pontine myelinolysis. Magnetic resonance (MRI) And computed tomography (CT) of brain were done which showed normal grey/white matter differentiation of both cerebral hemispheres, No mass effect or midline shift. No evidence of pontine myelinolysis was found. Disequilibrium syndrome was declared in a patient was already on regular hemodialysis. However, Serum Osmolality = (2 x (Na + K)) + (BUN / 2.8) + (glucose / 18), the aggressive drop of serum BUN was compensated by sudden rise of serum sodium, daily calculated osmolality was not in major change to precipitate DDS. Method(s): case report Results Conclusion(s): DDS is a serious complication of hemodialysis and not only confined to the first hemodialysis session but as well can occur at any time in patients on intermittent dialysis.Copyright © 2020
