265. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 631732599
T1  - An interesting case of pulmonary arteriovenous malformation-a case report
T3  - Intern Section of the Royal Academy of Medicine in Ireland, RAMI 2019. Dublin Ireland.
A1  - Sheehan F.
A1  - Lally S.
A1  - Galvin J. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background: Pulmonary arteriovenous malformations (PAVMs) are aberrant communications between a pulmonary artery and vein, which lead to right-to-left shunt1. Recent studies suggest that these structural anomalies are more common in the general population than previously described, particularly amongst women. They estimated a prevalence of 1 in 26302. This is significant due to the associated risk of paradoxical embolic stroke.3,4 We present the case of a 60 year old lady who was admitted with a four day history of progressive dyspnea on exertion, and fatigue. She was a smoker of 35 years but had no other past medical history. On examination of the lungs bi-basal crepitations were noted, no murmurs were appreciated on auscultation of the praecordium. She was saturating at 88% on room air and her respiratory rate was 24. Her bloods were all within in normal limits except for her D-dimer which was 3389. An ECG indicated new onset atrial fibrillation with a fast ventricular rate of 130bpm and the chest X-Ray highlighted increased ground glass infiltrate in the mid and lower zones bilaterally. An ABG demonstrated a; pH of 7.46, pCO2 of 3.2 and PO2 of 6.6. The initial clinical impressionwas of pulmonary embolus so she had a CTPAwhich, unexpectedly, highlighted a simple-type left lower lobe PAVM, with a 6mmdiameter feeding artery. An Echo showed an ejection fraction of 35%, significant mitral stenosis, moderate mitral regurgitation and flow across IAS with left to right shunting. Conclusion(s): Definitive treatment is not needed for all patients with PAVMs. The patient's co-morbities and the diameter of the feeding artery, are all factors to consider5-6. In cases where treatment is deemed necessary, embolotherapy is the mainstay7. In this case a decision was made for embolization with a vascular plug as it allows for precise deployment and safe occlusion of the PAVM8.
