266. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 631518222
T1  - The safety of PEG in patients with ALS using non-invasive positive pressure ventilation: A retrospective study
T3  - 30th International Symposium on ALS/MND. Perth, WA Australia.
A1  - Tominaga N.
A1  - Shimizu T.
A1  - Uchino A.
A1  - Ogino Y.
A1  - Ogino M. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background: In amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), respiratory dysfunction and dysphasia appears in addition to limb weakness. Previous study showed that ALS patients shows hypermetabolism in the early stage of the disease, and malnutrition at the time of diagnosis is shown to be one of the poor prognostic factors in ALS. Keeping good nutritional status by tube feeding is of importance to improve QOL and prognosis. Since PCO2 < 50 Torr or %FVC> 50% has been recommended as the PEG period, there are some cases who were judged unable to undergo PEG due to respiratory failure. and such cases choose nasal feeding. In our hospital, about 90% of ALS patients choose PEG and most of cases undergo PEG under non-invasive positive pressure ventilation (NPPV). Objective(s): To clarify the safety of PEG in patients with ALS using NPPV. Method(s): We retrospectively reviewed the complications of endoscopic PEG under NPPV in our ALS. Eighty patients received endoscopic PEG in our hospital from 1 April 2014 to 16 November 2017. We compared the occurrence after pneumonia or other adverse events in 22 ALS patients received PEG under NPPV with 43 patients with intractable neurological disease including ALS without respiratory assistance (non-NPPV group). Result(s): Among 22 patients who received PEG under NPPV, no cases showed pneumonia within 1 month after surgery, and 6 patients showed mild to severe anemia. On the other hand, in the non-NPPV group, 8 out of 43 cases showed pneumonia, and no cases showed anemia. One case in the non-NPPV group showed respiratory disturbance during surgery, which improved only by medication without respiratory assistance . Discussion and conclusion: Our results suggest that PEG could be safely performed in patients with ALS under NPPV compared with ALS with preserved raspiratory function or patients with other intractable neurological diseases.
