A1  - English W. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Class III Obesity, defined as a Body Mass Index (BMI) > 40 prohibits patients with Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) from being eligible for kidney transplantation. Surgical gastric bypass involves reducing the size of the stomach and reconnecting the smaller stomach to bypass the first portion of the small intestine. This restricts food intake and reduces caloric absorption, resulting in weight loss. We present the following case of one study participant who underwent surgical gastric bypass in 2015. After successful weight loss, the patient underwent a deceased donor kidney transplant (DDKT) in August 2018. Aug 2014: KD, a 32 y.o. Caucasian female, presented for kidney transplant evaluation. History: HTN, PCOS, GERD, Class III Obesity, ESRD on hemodialysis (01/2014) Ht: 155 cm Wt: 111 kg BMI: 46.9 Labs: Hgb 11.0, Alb. 3.6 Patient was interested in and qualified for surgical gastric bypass. The Kidney Transplant Program at Vanderbilt University Medical Center offers a research study option for those patients with a BMI >40 who are interested to lose weight for kidney transplantation. Patients are randomized to one of two groups: Surgical Gastric Bypass or Medical Weight Loss Management. Informed consent was obtained, patient began to follow study protocol. Dec. 2014: Bariatric Initial Consultation for Roux en Y Gastric Bypass Wt: 101.4 kg BMI: 42.1 Alb. 4.1, Hgb 11.8 April 2015: Laparoscopic Roux en Y Gastric Bypass Wt: 98.5 kg BMI: 41 Post op day 1: Alb. 2.9, Hgb 10.3 May 2016: 1-year post-op Wt: 51.3 kg BMI: 21 Alb. 4.0, Hgb 10.6 August 2018: DDKT Wt: 48.2 kg BMI 20 Alb. 4.2, Hgb 14.6 There were no major adverse events after bariatric surgery. Diet, medications, electrolytes and volume status were managed with post bariatric protocols modified to account for complexities of ESRD. The case presented here illustrates the success that can be achieved using surgical gastric bypass to achieve weight loss to meet BMI criteria to qualify for kidney transplant.Copyright © 2019 Published by Elsevier
