280. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2001485683
T1  - Anorexigenic peptide (leptin, obestatin, nesfatin-1) levels and their impact on IVF/ICSI outcome in patients with polycystic ovary syndrome
T3  - 26th EBCOG European Congress of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Paris France.
A1  - Varli B.
A1  - Ozmen B.
A1  - Erguder B.I.
A1  - Sukur Y.E.
A1  - Atabekoglu C.
A1  - Sonmezer M.
A1  - Berker B. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Introduction: Reproductive system is controlled strictly by both brain and periferic tissues. Some mediators take role in these communication. Anorexigenic peptides are one of these messengers and their levels on patients with PCOS are not known widely and there are conflicting results in literature Objective: To show differences in anorexigenic peptide levels in patients with or without Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) and determine their effects on IVF/ICSI outcome. Method(s): Total of 83 patients was included in the study. PCOS group consist of 41 patients and non-PCOS group consist of 42 patients. Patients in PCOS group were diagnosed according to 2003 Rotterdam criteria. Non-PCOS group patients were admitted for IVF/ICSI cycle for male infertility, tubal factor or unexplained infertility. ICSI were performed for severe male infertility. Controlled ovarian hyper stimulation was done with either GnRH agonist or antagonist protocol. On the third day of menstrual cycle, before administration of exogenous gonadotropins, venous blood samples were taken to determine serum anorexigenic peptide levels. ELISA method was used in determination of serum anorexigenic peptide levels. Discussion and conclusions: Patient characteristics and BMI levels were similar among groups. In patients with PCOS, serum obestatin levels were significantly lower than the control group. Serum anorexigenic peptide levels did not differ between patients with or without clinical pregnancy as seen in table. There were no OHSS in control group but mild OHSS were diagnosed in four patients in PCOS group. Obestatin levels in patients with OHSS were significantly lower than other patients. There were no correlation between anorexigenic peptide levels and clinical pregnancy rates in our study and this makes these peptides useless in prediction of IVF/ICSI outcome. Only obestatin levels can be used in prediction of OHSS.Copyright © 2018
