308. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 638108948
T1  - PREVALENCE AND PREDICTORS OF OLIGOMENORRHEA AND AMENORRHEA IN DIVISION 1 FEMALE ATHLETES
T3  - 74th Annual Congress of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine, ASRM 2018. Denver, CO United States.
A1  - Verrilli L.
A1  - Blanchard H.
A1  - Landry M.
A1  - Stanic A. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: Long-term health is impacted by disorders of hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian (HPO) axis that frequently manifest as oligomenorrhea and amenorrhea. Elite female athletes represent a group who may be at higher risk of HPO disorders. Despite long-standing observations that strenuous exercise, stress and weight impact the HPO axis, little is known the prevalence and predictors of oligo/amenorrhea in this population.Consequently, there exists a need for a comprehensive dataset to explore menstrual patterns and systemic hormone use in elite athletes. We conducted a cross sectional survey study in order to answer these questions. DESIGN: This is a descriptive online cross-sectional survey study. This is a subset analysis of a larger study by the same group of investigators. MATERIALS AND METHODS: This survey was distributed to 455 Division 1 Female athletes at the University of Wisconsin via an online platform. Statistical analysis was performed in STATA and JMP by the Obstetrics and Gynecology statistics team. Bivariate chi square and descriptive statistical analysis was performed. RESULT(S): Response rate was 49% with a total of 224 respondents. Average self-reported age was 20 and BMI (based on height/weight) was 22. The athletes reported 11 different sports with endurance athletes representing 57% of all respondents. Eumenorrhea (reported menstrual cycles every 4 weeks) was reported by 67%. Rate of amenorrhea was 5% and rate of oligomenorrhea was 24%. 5% of women reported bleeding more than every two weeks. Underweight athletes (BMI<20) were not more likely to be oligomenorrheic or amenorrheic when compared with athletes of normal BMI or overweight athletes, however, all amenorrheic athletes had BMI of less than 25. Cross country and track athletes were more likely to be underweight when compared with the eleven other sports (22%, p< 0.02). Underweight athletes were less likely to use a systemic hormonal contraceptive method when compared with normal and overweight athletes (29%, p< 0.03). Our study design does not distinguish between WHO type I and II amenorrhea, so some athletes studied may have PCOS instead of more typical hypothalamic anovulation, a question we will explore in the future. CONCLUSION(S): This study provides further evidence of menstrual dysfunction in elite female athletes. Overall prevalence of menstrual dysfunction in our cohort was 33%, which is higher than prior studies quoted in the literature. Menstrual dysfunction occurs regardless of BMI, although it is important to note that all amenorrheic athletes had BMI <25, suggesting that disruption in the HPO axis can occur without decreased energy availability. Consequently, screening for female athlete triad should be broad and include athletes of normal BMI, as BMI alone may not be fully predictive of menstrual dysfunction. Finally, low uptake of systemic hormonal contraception by the underweight cohort is potentially troubling, due to long-term consequences of hypoestrogenemia, and suggests a target intervention group.
