313. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 630753209
T1  - A curious case of sweet smelling urine
T3  - National Conference on Education 2017. Chicago, IL United States.
A1  - York J.B.
A1  - Azuma D.
A1  - Bennett J.
A1  - Murray P.D. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Maple Syrup Urine Disease (MSUD) is an autosomal recessive inborn error of metabolism characterized by decreased enzymatic activity of branched-chain alpha-ketoacid dehydrogenase which leads to an inability to break down branched chain amino acids. It is critical for physicians to make a prompt diagnosis of metabolic disorders to decreased metabolic decompensations and mitigate long-term complications A 33 year old G2 P2 Indian woman with no known family history of MSUD gave birth to a 39 1/7 week old male via spontaneous vaginal delivery with APGAR scores of 9 and 9 at 1 and 5 minutes respectively. The pregnancy was uncomplicated with unremarkable prenatal labs. Initial newborn exam was significant for hypospadias. The infant voided at birth without difficulty and breastfed well. Within 18 hours the mother noticed her infant's sweet smelling urine . Because of concerns for MSUD, the medical team made the infant NPO and started him on dextrose containing IV fluids. The newborn screen was sent STAT to the state lab and the infant was brought to the NICU. The infant did not have any changes in his physical exam. CBC and chemistry were within normal limits, including ammonia level (75 ug/dL) and capillary blood gas (pH 7.42, pCO2 38 mmHg, bicarbonate 25 mEq/L). Within 12 hours of stopping breast feeding, the urine no longer had a sweet odor. The newborn screen came back negative for MSUD and breast milk was re-started. With further discussion, it was learned that the mother supplemented her diet with fenugreek. The week prior to delivery she also began taking fenugreek supplements to enhance milk supply. Fenugreek contains sotolon, the same compound responsible for the sweet smell in MSUD. This case illustrates the importance of the complete history including non-prescription supplements. Although most mothers begin taking lactation supplements after the child is born, it is important to take cultural practices into consideration. By recognizing the potential for sweet smelling urine when fenugreek supplementation is initiated, we can prevent unnecessary tests, increased time spent away from the mothers and an unneeded interruption in breast feeding. Dietary practices should be explored when MSUD is in the differential diagnosis.
