317. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 624607727
T1  - The anovulation due hypothalamic amenorrhea
T3  - 22nd FIGO World Congress of Gynecology and Obstetrics. Rio de Janeiro Brazil.
A1  - Diaz I. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - The anovulation due hypothalamic amenorrhea is a form frequent of chronic anovulation, associated with stress, weight loss, excessive exercise, or a combination thereof. Anorexia and bulimia nervosa induced alterations in gonadotropin secretion, particularly luteinizing hormone. The prevalence of exercise-induced amenorrhea varies from 5% to 40%-50% in elite runners (Germain N et al.2017) Endogenous opioids play a major role in the central nervous system their inhibitory effects on pulsatile GnRH secretion from the hypothalamus. In women an increase of endogenous opioids has been shown following times of stress, starvation, and anorexia nervosa, as reflected by the inhibition of the hypothalamic pulse generator and resulting in a decline of circulating levels of FSH and LH results in anovulation (Bottcher B 2018). There are in association between patients with HA and polycystic ovary syndrome (Santoro N. J 2011). Treatment must include consumption, and/or improved nutrition, and/or decreased exercise activity, psychological support. Oral contraceptive pills for the sole purpose of regaining menses or improving BMD. One short-term use of transdermal E2 therapy with cyclic oral in adolescents and women who have not had return of menses after a reasonable trial of nutritional, psychological, and/or modified exercise intervention. In patients with HA wishing to conceive the treatment with pulsatile gonadotropin-releasing hormone as a first line, followed by gonadatropin therapy and induction of ovulation when GnRH is not available and only induce have a BMI of at least 18.5 kg/m2 and only after attempts to normalize energy balance (Gordon et al. 2017).
