320. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 623816082
T1  - Electrolyte disturbance in eating disorder
T3  - 9th Congress of the World Federation of Pediatric Intensive and Critical Care Societies, WFPICCS 2018. Singapore Singapore.
A1  - Freeman J.
A1  - Ardill R. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Aims & Objectives: A 14 year old boy was admitted to PICU following an out of hospital cardiac arrest. Methods He was found to be in Ventricular Tachycardia and 1 x DC shock was given. On arrival to hospital venous blood gas showed severe hypocholaraemic hypokalaemic metabolic alkalosis. Results PH 7.89, PCO2 2.4, NA+126, K + 1.5, Cl82. BE +ve 18. An ECG demonstrated a prolonged QTC of 675ms. An echo confirmed that the heart was structurally normal. On admission the patients GCS was 4 therefore he was intubated and ventilated. Metabolic and genetic investigations were normal. An abdominal USS and small bowel contrast study were normal. The patient was gradually hydrated and electrolyte disturbance was corrected over the 48 hours. Upon waking the patient disclosed that he had struggled with body image and perceptions about his weight for the last 3 years. His enteral intake had been good but he would induce vomiting after every meal. He denied laxative use but admitted to drinking highly caffeinated drinks to keep his energy levels up. Conclusions A history of chronic vomiting fits with the profound hypokalaemic metabolic acidosis observed on admission. Interestingly the first gas was taken following arrest and the PH and potassium may have been higher and lower respectively. Theoretically the patient will have started to correct his alkalosis and increase his potassium levels by arresting. Eating disorders in male paediatric patients is an increasing problem with high morbidity, mortality and poor prognosis. This case highlights the importance of early support for affected individuals.
