321. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622968873
T1  - High velocity nasal insufflation in hypercapneic respiratory failure: Secondary analysis of randomized clinical trial
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2018. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Dodge D.
A1  - Whittle J.S.
A1  - Bublewicz M.B.
A1  - Kearney J.
A1  - Ashe T.
A1  - Harsch M.
A1  - Dungan G.
A1  - Miller T.L.
A1  - Doshi P. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Rationale: High flow nasal cannula (HFNC) has been shown to be effective in providing respiratory support that is greater than traditional nasal cannula. The effectiveness of HFNC is based on its ability to provide extra-thoracic dead space clearance in addition to upwards of 100% oxygen and potentially mild distending pressure. High velocity nasal insufflation (HVNI) is a form of HFNC which utilizes small bore nasal cannula to optimize the efficiency of dead space purge. HFNC has been shown to be effective in hypoxic respiratory failure and in post-extubation support. However, its role and effectiveness in hypercapnic respiratory failure has not been well established. The goal of this study is to assess the ability of HVNI as compared to non-invasive positive pressure ventilation (NIPPV) to provide ventilatory support to patients presenting to the emergency department (ED) with acute hypercapnic respiratory failure. Method(s): This is a secondary analysis of a prospective, multi-center, randomized clinical trial of patients presenting with respiratory failure to the ED requiring NIPPV. Patients were randomized to HVNI (initial flow, 35 L.min-1; temperature, 35degree-37degreeC; fraction of inspired oxygen, 1.0) versus NIPPV using an oronasal mask (inspiratory positive airway pressure, 10 cmH20; expiratory positive airway pressure, 5 cmH20) and followed for primary outcome of therapy failure, assessed by intubation or cross over to the other therapy. Management independent of the study interventions was per standard care in each facility. The subgroup of patients presenting with hypercapneic respiratory failure were analyzed for this study. Primary endpoints were therapy failure/success, and secondary analysis were physiologic indices of ventilation. Result(s): A total of 204 patients were enrolled in the primary study, of which 65 presented with hypercapnic respiratory failure; 34 in the HVNI group and 31 in the NIPPV group. The intubation rate was 5.9% in the HVNI group and 16.1% in the NIPPV group and the failure of assigned arm or crossover rate was 23.5% in the HVNI group and 12.9% in the NIPPV group. The impact of HVNI on PCO2 and respiratory rate over time was similar to that of NIPPV in this cohort. There were no differences in ED, ICU and overall hospital length of stay between groups. Conclusion(s): This study demonstrates that HVNI is able to provide ventilatory support similar to NIPPV in patients presenting with hypercapnic respiratory failure. Further study is needed to corroborate these findings.
