322. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622965916
T1  - A novel mutation in the sfptc gene in a newborn with persistent tachypnea
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2018. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Agrawal S.
A1  - De A.
A1  - Hamvas A.
A1  - Arens R. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Introduction: Pulmonary surfactant plays a key role in gas exchange by preventing collapse of alveoli. Genetic abnormalities associated with surfactant production or recycling can lead to surfactant dysfunction. Surfactant disorders should be suspected in babies who present with respiratory distress in the newborn period. Case: A 7-day old girl born at 37 weeks of gestation to a 35 year old multigravida via Cesarian Section with Apgar scores of 9 and 9 with uneventful perinatal course, but was admitted for evaluation due to recurrent episodes of cyanosis while feeding and with activity. She was afebrile, respiratory rate 60-100 breaths/min, with SpO2 83- 98% on room air. Chest auscultation was remarkable for shortened inspiratory expiratory ratio. CXR showed low lung volumes with bilateral diffuse reticular pattern. An echocardiogram demonstrated an aberrant right subclavian artery. Infectious work up was negative. A chest CT angiogram showed no evidence of vascular ring but dependent haziness was noted on both lungs. A venous blood gas on 6 LPM high flow 0.5 FiO2 revealed PCO2 68 and PO2 30. There was positive history of transient neonatal respiratory distress in two siblings that self-resolved. Given persistent tachypnea and hypoxemia, interstitial lung findings, and the family history, DNA surfactant panel sequencing was obtained. Results showed a novel variant in c.494-495delAG in exon 5 of the surfactant pulmonary-associated protein C (SFTPC). The child was discharged within 2-weeks on 0.25-0.5 LPM supplemental oxygen via nasal cannula. Oxygen was completely weaned off by 5 months of age, and she is thriving well at 8 months of age without any additional medications. Genetic testing for the parents and siblings is in progress. Discussion(s): The 197 amino acid SP-C proprotein is encoded by a ~3.5 kbase gene localized to Chromosome 8. This variant in the BRICHOS domain in the 3' terminus is not present in the Exome Aggregate Consortium database (ExAC, http://exac.broadinstitute.org/gene/ENSG00000168484) of over 60,000 individuals and is predicted to result in elongation of the SP-C proprotein by 4 amino acids. Missense variants in the BRICHOS domain disrupt the normal itinerary of the proprotein and lead to intracellular amyloid accumulation and chronic lung disease. This child's respiratory symptoms improved with supportive care only, as has been reported in ~ 1/3 of the children with respiratory disease associated with pathogenic variants in SFTPC. While it is likely this variant contributed to this child's presentation, the exact mechanism of disease remains to be determined.
