327. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622308181
T1  - Small fiber neuropathy and multiple endocrinopathies with COX6A1 gene deletion
T3  - 70th Annual Meeting of the American Academy of Neurology, AAN 2018. Los Angeles, Ca United States.
A1  - Cook G.
A1  - Crimmins M.
A1  - Turner C. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Objective: Describe a case of small fiber neuropathy, hypothyroidism, and polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) with heterozygous deletion of COX6A1. Background(s): COX6A1 codes for the 6A1 subunit of cytochrome C oxidase, the final enzyme in the mitochondrial electron transport chain. Homozygous mutations of COX6A1 have been reported in Charcot-Marie-Tooth type D. Large deletions of COX6A1 have not previously been reported. Design/Methods: Clinical and laboratory findings in a woman with small fiber neuropathy and heterozygous COX6A1 deletion are presented. Result(s): A 32-year-old woman presented with orthostatic intolerance, fainting, anorexia, early satiety, and intermittent incomplete bladder emptying. She had progressive graying of hair in her early teenage years with more recent thinning hair. She also had hypothyroidism and PCOS. Physical examination showed sluggish pupillary constriction, decreased peripheral visual acuity, and distalpredominant decreased sensation to pinprick and temperature. Quantitative sweat testing demonstrated decreased to absent response at all sites. Heart rate response to deep breathing and heart rate and blood pressure responses to Valsalva maneuver were normal. There was no orthostatic hypotension; there was supine tachycardia with a normal orthostatic increase. Prolonged tilt test provoked a "vasovagal" event with prominent vasodepressor but no cardioinhibitory response. Epidermal nerve fiber density was borderline low in the calf and foot with decreased sweat gland nerve fiber density at the leg and no sweat glands identified in the foot. Sequencing/deletion analysis of the mitochondrial genome and sequencing/deletion/duplication analysis of nuclear genes related to mitochondrial function revealed a heterozygous deletion of the entire COX6A1 gene. Other variants of uncertain significance were present. Conclusion(s): Deletion of COX6A1 may be related to small fiber neuropathies. The causal relationship in this case remains uncertain. Further testing with functional studies of COX activity or ATP levels or testing of family members for segregation analysis may help differentiate pathogenicity.
