364. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 619349746
T1  - Factors affecting 1-month mortality after gastrostomy placement
T3  - 28th International Symposium on ALS/MND. Boston, MA United States.
A1  - Trdina P.
A1  - Koritnik B.
A1  - Leonardis L.
A1  - Groselj L.D.
A1  - Plut S.
A1  - Klinar P.
A1  - Kovacic S.R.
A1  - Perme M.P.
A1  - Pavlic K.
A1  - Zidar J. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Background: Percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy (PEG) is a well-established procedure in patients with ALS with feeding problems. Although recommendations exist on when in the course of the disease to perform the PEG tube placement (1), it is not known exactly when the possible long-term benefits of PEG outweigh the periprocedural risks. Method(s): We performed a retrospective analysis of PEG in patients with ALS at the Ljubljana ALS Centre between January 2003 and June 2016. We analysed patients' demographic data, clinical features and progression of the disease, respiratory status, including the use of noninvasive ventilation (NIV) and decrease of body mass index (BMI). Comparisons were made between two groups of patients: those surviving less than one month (51mo group) and those surviving more than one month after the procedure (41mo group). The51mo group was also compared to a comparable group of patients without PEG. Result(s): During the observed period, 419 patients were seen at our ALS centre. PEG tube was inserted in 148 patients (35% of all patients). The procedure was performed at our hospital in 122 out of 148, and these patients were further analysed. 18 patients (15%) died within one month after PEG placement. Comparing the 51mo to the 41mo group, the following statistically significant differences were found. In the 51mo group, there were more spinal onset patients (72% vs 41%), ALSFRS-r score at PEG placement was lower (20.4 vs 26.0), a higher proportion was using NIV at PEG (28% vs 25%), arterial blood gas analysis showed higher pCO2 (5.97 kPa vs 5.55 kPa), lower pO2 (9.89 kPa vs 10.94 kPa) and higher base excess (4.62 mEq/l vs 2.58 mEq/l). Survival from disease symptom onset was shorter in the 51mo group (24.5 months vs 38.5 months). BMI at the beginning of the disease was comparable in both groups (25 kg/m2 vs 25.8 kg/m2) but greater BMI decrease at the time of PEG insertion was found in the 51mo group (5.4 kg/m2; 0.7 kg/m2 per month vs 3.4 kg/m2; 0.4 kg/m2 per month). Discussion(s): According to our results, factors associated with increased 1-month mortality after gastrostomy placement are spinal-onset ALS, increased functional impairment, decreased respiratory function and decreased BMI. The peri-procedural mortality rate (15%) was higher than expected from the natural progression of the disease and is comparable to some of the published retrospective studies (13% (2), 12.9% (3) and 10.4% (4)). Our data shows which factors contribute to the peri-procedural risks of PEG. It remains to be answered in which patients these risks are lower than the long-term benefits of PEG.
