A1  - Oelberg D. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Malignant peritoneal mesothelioma is an aggressive and rare neoplasm with low incidence and poor prognosis. About 3,000 new cases of mesothelioma are diagnosed each year in the United States. The worldwide incidence is approximately 8-12 cases per 100,000 persons per year. Only 20% to 33% of all mesotheliomas arise from the peritoneum itself; the pleura is the most common site of origin. CASE PRESENTATION: We report a case of a 37-year-old female who presented to the emergency room with progressive shortness of breath and chest pain. There was no associated cough, hemoptysis, weight loss or anorexia. Her past medical history includes asthma, PCOS and infertility. Patient's initial workup revealed a RLL small right pleural effusion on portable chest x-ray. A CTA was performed which did not show any gross central pulmonary artery emboli but multiple irregular, nodular, and enhancing soft tissue masses were appreciated along the right parietal pleural and diaphragmatic surfaces with no significant hilar or mediastinal lymphadenopathy were seen. CT of abdomen and pelvis was performed which revealed bilateral complex adnexal masses associated with abdominal and pelvic ascites as well as cul-de-sac nodules.Mesenteric adenopathy was demonstrated along with a large mass in the porta hepatis as well as a large right-sided retroperitoneal mass compressing the inferior vena cava and the left renal vein. A lymph node biopsy was successfully executed which revealed fragments of fibrous connective tissue infiltrated by a malignant neoplasm composed of highly atypical epithelioid cells arranged in tubulopapillary structures. Immunohistochemical stains demonstrate immunoreactivity of the neoplastic cells for mesothelial markers. These results further support the diagnosis of malignant mesothelioma of the epithelioid type. DISCUSSION: MPM is often considered a disease of the elderly with a median age of 74 years. Patients with malignant peritoneal mesothelioma often present late in disease process and often are difficult to diagnose due to unspecific symptoms presenting overtime. It is a rare diagnosis in young adults in view that the latency period between exposure and diagnosis is as short as 13 years or as long as 70. It has been reported that almost 15% of cases with MPM were younger than the age 40. CONCLUSION(S): A multi-disciplinarian team approach in this case was crucial to obtain a diagnosis. The importance of distinguishing peritoneal mesothelioma lies not only in the histologic differences of this tumor, but the clinical presentation and precise and accurate diagnostic approach. Our patient has been undergoing treatment to this day.
