T1  - NUCB2 nesfatin- 1 alterations in children with and without Helicobacter pylori Gastritis
T3  - 29th International Workshop on Helicobacter and Microbiota in Inflammation and Cancer. Magdeburg Germany.
A1  - Ugras M.
A1  - Aydin S.
A1  - Asik G.
A1  - Akoluk A.
A1  - Bicer S.
A1  - Bicer A. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - The recently discovered NUCB2/nesfatin- 1 is regulated by hunger and satiety and its middle segment (M30) is responsible for limiting food intake. NUCB2/nesfatin- 1 and NUCB2 mRNA levels were localized in almost all biological tissues, including gastric mucosa and higher than brain tissues. H. pylori isknown to cause gastritis, peptic ulcer disease and may also cause reduction of body weight, pain, among children. Therefore, purpose of this study was to evaluate serum NUCB2/ nesfatin- 1 in children with and without H. pylori gastritis. We diagnosed subjects on the basis of presence ( n: 35) or absence ( n: 22) of the H. pylori gastritis according to ESPGHAN/ NASPGHAN guidelines. Exclusion criteria were as follows: children with known diabetes, obesity, epilepsy, CNS anomaly and polycystic ovary syndrome. The average age of children with H. Pylori gastritis and control was 12.9 +/- 2.6 and 11.1 +/- 2.5, respectively. The serum NUCB2/nesfatin- 1 level was higher than for healthy individuals' 12.1 +/- 2.1 ng/mL in patients with H. pylori gastritis (13.9 +/- 2.2 ng/mL). The weight, height and z scores for weight and height are were given Table 1. There is no relationship between serum NUCB2/nesfatin- 1 levels and weight, height or z scores for either weight or height in children. High NUCB2/nesfatin- 1 levels might not be a causative factor for appetite or weight alterations observed in children with H. pylori gastritis.
