406. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 613521856
T1  - Ketoacidosis in a breast-feeding patient on the paleolithic diet
T3  - 46th Critical Care Congress of the Society of Critical Care Medicine, SCCM 2016. Honolulu, HI United States.
A1  - Diamond E.
A1  - Beri S.
A1  - Perez E.
A1  - Ameer F. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - Learning Objectives: We discuss a rarely reported case of lactation ketoacidosis in humans. Method(s): A 31-year-old gravida 2, para 2, 16-weeks postpartum, lactating female presented with a 2-day history of shortness of breath, vomiting, and weakness. Postpartum care was remarkable for an intentional 20-lb weight loss on the "Paleolithic diet," over the previous 2 months. Recommended by her dermatologist for eczema treatment, the Paleo diet consisted of fruits, vegetables, and mostly fish but without carbohydrates. In addition, she was breastfeeding her newborn child, producing 70 oz. of milk per day on average, three times the upper limit of normal. On presentation, respiratory rate was 24 breaths/min, but physical exam was otherwise unremarkable. Lab results were significant for an arterial blood gas with pH of 7.108, pCo2 11.7, pO2 142.3, HCo3 3.7. Anion gap was 26 with lactic acid of 1.9, Beta-hydroxybutarate was markedly elevated over 7.96, and Hemoglobin A1c of 4.5. D-dimer was 270. A comprehensive drug screen was negative including salicylates, ethanol and acetaminophen. Insulin level was suppressed and cortisol level was appropriate. Chest radiograph and CT Angiography were normal. The patient was transferred to the ICU and treated with aggressive fluid resuscitation with 3 ampules of NaHCo3 in D5W at 150 cc/ hr for 24 hours. A regular diet was started and breastfeeding stopped. Her symptoms and acidosis rapidly improved within 24 hours of admission. Her anion gap closed and beta-hydroxybutarate normalized within 48 hours. Patient was transferred to the general medical floor and discharged from the hospital on Day 4 on a normal diet, multivitamin supplements and instructions to stop breast-feeding. Result(s): Similar to prior reports, our patient was under the stress of lactation but the degree of her acidosis, a serum pH of 7.0, has rarely been reported. We feel that in her case, the Paleolithic low carbohydrate diet and subsequent weight loss precipitated the ketoacidosis and the increased metabolic demands of lactation produced a life-threatening acidemia.
