AN  - 612867934
T1  - The association between body mass index and androgen levels in adolescent girls with irregular menses or amenorrhea
T3  - ASRM Scientific Congress and Expo Scaling New Heights in Reproductive Medicine, ASRM 2016. Salt Lake City, UT United States.
A1  - Davis-Kankanamge C.N.
A1  - Strickland J.
A1  - Carnahan M.
A1  - Higgins J.
A1  - Dowlut-McElroy T. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: To evaluate the correlation between body mass index (BMI) and biochemical androgen levels in adolescent girls with irregular menstrual cycles and amenorrhea. DESIGN: Retrospective cohort review. MATERIALS AND METHODS: Following institutional review board approval, we queried a pediatric hospital's medical database from January 1999 to September 2014 and identified all girls ages 9 to 18 years with a diagnosis of oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea (ICD-9 codes 626.0 and 626.1). Each medical record was reviewed to obtain demographics, menstrual history, gynecologic age (chronological age minus age at menarche), BMI, androgen and gonadotropin levels, as well as associated thyroid and prolactin levels. Use of combined oral contraceptives or other hormonal treatment in the 3 months prior to presentation, history of eating disorders or malignancy, ovarian tumors, Cushing syndrome, and non-classical adrenal hyperplasia were cause for exclusion. Data were analyzed descriptively. Multivariate associations of predictors related to androgen levels were assessed via binary logistic regression analysis. Statistical significance was defined as p < 0.05 and analyses were performed using SPSS version 22.0 (SPSS Inc., Chicago, IL). RESULT(S): A total of 1100 charts were reviewed, of which 422 met inclusion criteria and were available for data analysis. The mean age of girls included was 15 +/- 1.5 years. The mean gynecologic age was 3 +/- 1.7 years. The mean BMI was 30 +/- 9 kg/m2. The adjusted odds of having elevated testosterone (defined as total testosterone > 40ng/dL) for girls categorized as overweight (BMI percentage of 85-95%) were not statistically significant (OR 1.6, 95% CI 0.7, 3.6; p=0.274) when luteinizing hormone and folliclestimulating hormone (LH/FSH) and gynecologic age were controlled. However, for obese girls (BMI >=95%), the odds of having elevated testosterone were significantly greater, again when LH/FSH and gynecologic age were controlled. Compared to underweight/normal weight girls, the odds of having an elevated testosterone for obese girls were 2.8 times greater (95% CI 1.5, 5.3; p=0.001). CONCLUSION(S): In adolescent girls, obesity appears to be an independent risk factor for elevated total testosterone levels. The use of elevated testosterone as an independent marker for diagnosis of polycystic ovary syndrome may not be appropriate for obese adolescent girls near menarche. Further research is needed to evaluate the association between obesity, hyperandrogenism, and oligomenorrhea in adolescent girls.
