413. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 612138731
T1  - Essential anatomy for cervical spine surgery: Frequency of collateral flow to vertebrobasilar region evaluated with digital subtraction angiography
T3  - EUROSPINE Meeting 2016. Berlin Germany.
A1  - Aoyama T.
A1  - Obara N. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - Introduction: Cervical spine surgery possess a risk of vertebral artery(VA) injury. One side VA injury usually doesn't leads to serious complication, since there are some collateral flow circulation in cerebral vessels. Posterior communicating artery(PcomA) is a part of Willis arterial circle, supply blood flow from internal carotid artery( ICA) to vertebro-basilar artery region. And both side VAs join and compose basilar artery(BA), so the opposite side VA can work as bypass. However, some cases are lacking of these collateral flow. For evaluation of cerebral vessels, there are some methods like MR or CT angiography. Digital subtraction angiography(DSA) is a little bit invasive, but can detect subtle artery, flow direction. So DSA is gold standard for evaluation of cerebral vessels. Frequency of PcomA, VA union, and other abnormality relating to VA injury risk are investigated in this study. Material(s) and Method(s): DSA of consecutive 240 cases between July 2013 and December 2015 are analysed retrospectively. They were 119 man and 121 woman, age was 13-94yrs(67.8 +/- 15.4). Reasons receiving DSA were cerebral aneurysms, brain tumors, cerebral ischemic disease, etc. Since invasiveness, vessls only necessary are investigated. So some patients didn't receive 4 vessels study. And if the artery was occluded, it couldn't be catheterized. Patients, in whom only one side VA or ICA can be evaluated, are excluded. Equipment of DSA was Artis zee TA (SIEMENS AG). Result(s): 157 cases received carotid angiography. Of them, 53 cases(33 %) were lacking of both sides PcomA. Only 104cases(67 %) had one or both sides collateral flow from anterior to VA-BA region. Of these104 cases, PcomA of 7 cases were fetal type PcomA: posterior cerebral artery is fed only by PcomA. Fetal type PcomA can't be collateral to VA-BA region. From these, collateral flow can't be expected in 38 % cases. And 149 cases received vertebral angiography. Of them, there were VA union in 125 cases(84 %). In 8 cases(5 %), only one side VA existed, and in 16 cases(11 %), one side VA were PICA end VA which terminates as posterior inferior cerebellar artery and doesn't join with the other side VA. In 16 % cases, dominant side VA injury can cause VA-BA region ischemia. Furthermore, there were high risk cases were found. In 4 cases, both side PcomA and VA union were not described. Of them 2 cases were lacking of one side VA, and 2 cases were PICA end VA. For such situation, dominant VA injury is fatal. Conclusion(s): Willis arterial circle and VA union are collateral vessels to VA-BA region. This DSA study reveals that collateral flow can't be expected from anterior circulation in 38 % cases, from the other side VA in 16 % cases. Preoperative evaluation of cerebral vessels is essential for cervical spine surgery. And surgical strategy should be considered with the condition of vessels.
