415. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72321831
T1  - Increase in perceived stress distinguishes severity of menstrual disruption in young women in response to a 3 month diet and exercise intervention
T3  - Experimental Biology 2016, EB. San Diego, CA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Williams N.I.
A1  - Lieberman J.
A1  - De Souza M.J. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - Low energy availability and psychosocial stress can independently and in combination disrupt reproductive function in mammalian species. However, prospective studies demonstrating both of these effects in humans are rare. We previously showed a causal link between low energy availability and the total number of induced menstrual disturbances (luteal phase defects, oligomenorrhea, and anovulation) in previously sedentary women in response to a 3 month diet and exercise intervention. In the current analysis we tested whether changes in perceived stress (Cohen, 1983) also contributed to the observed menstrual disturbances. Forty previously sedentary women age 18-24 yrs, BMI 51-69 kg/m2, gynecological age 4-15 yrs completed approximately 3 months of a diet and exercise protocol where original group assignment was to either a group that maintained energy balance or one of four groups at varying combinations of diet and exercise manipulated to create low to severe energy deficiency. All subjects ovulated during the baseline cycle prior to the onset of 3 months of supervised exercise (5X per week, moderate to vigorous aerobic exercise 20-75 min) and controlled feeding. Menstrual disturbances were assessed using daily urinary measures of estrone-1-glucuronide, pregnanediol glucuronide, and mid-cycle luteinizing hormone in addition to menstrual calendars. The intervention produced modest weight loss (0-4 kg) and expected increases in body composition and aerobic fitness. As previously reported, the magnitude of the energy deficit predicted the frequency but not the severity of menstrual disturbances such that the greater the energy deficit the greater the sum of all types of menstrual disturbances observed during the three month intervention. In the present analysis, subjects were divided into those who experienced a) no disturbances (NONE; n=14), b) either luteal phase defects and or oligomenorrheic cycles (36 days or greater)(LUT-OLIGO; n=13) or c) at least one anovulatory cycle (ANOV; n=10). The change from baseline to post study in perceived stress was significantly greater in ANOV vs. NONE and LUT-OLIGO: 10.1+/-3.6, 1.7+/- 1.7, -0.33+/- 1.9, respectively (P<0.05; ANOVA and post hoc LSD). All ANOV subjects also experienced either a luteal phase defect or an oligomenorrheic cycle during the intervention, and a higher proportion exhibited either a luteal phase defect or oligomenorrheic cycle at Baseline when compared to NONE and LUT-OLIGO (P<0.05; ANOV and post hoc LSD). These results suggest that increases in perceived stress may contribute to anovulation in the context of an exercise training program that is accompanied by weight loss.
