458. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72185946
T1  - Thiamine transporter-2 deficiency (hTHTR2). Case report
T3  - 12th World Congress of Perinatal Medicine 2015. Madrid Spain.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Perez Crespo M.D.R.
A1  - Vidal Esteban A.
A1  - Morales Betancourt P.C.
A1  - Blanco Perez R.
A1  - Cervera Bravo A.
A1  - Sanchez De Leon Arenas L. 
Y1  - 2015//
N2  - Introduction: The thiamine is an important substrate for the adequate function of the central nervous system. Thiamine transporter-2 deficiency, (hTHTR2) is a rare, inherited autosomal recessive disease, caused by mutations in the SLC19A3 gene. It manifest as acute or recurrent encephalopathy that might be associated with generalized dystonia. Case Summary: 27-day-old baby, was admitted in NICU because of irritability, crying, poor feeding, hyperexcitability, tremor, generalized hypertonia and intermittent opisthotonus. Sunset eyes. The fontanelles and the cranial nerves were normal. Uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery at 38 weeks of gestational age. Family history: third son of Moroccan parents (two previous healthy children); 2nd degree of consanguinity. One sister of the mother and 4 brothers of the father died before the age of 14. Blood count, acute phase reactants, urine analysis and cerebrospinal fluid were normal. Venous blood gases: pH 7.40; pCO2 21mmHg, HCO3 12,6mmol/L with high lactate levels (7,3mmol/L). Echocardiogram, cranial and abdominal ultrasounds were normal. Since the beginning the patient presented several episodes of generalized dystonia with isolated horizontal nystagmus in one of them. The cranial MRI showed signal alteration in the medial midbrainpontine region, lateral thalamic nuclei and in both corona radiata, fan shaped with a symmetricaldiffuse pattern. Normal awake and asleep EEG. Based on the biochemistry results (high levels of lactate and abnormal blood gases), the abnormalities on the neurological exploration and on MRI, treatment with thiamine, folic acid, vitamin B12, vitamin E, idebenone, biotin and vitamin C was started. After 48 hours of treatment, there was a dramatic improvement in the neurologic exploration. Additional results supported the presumptive diagnosis: lactate 5,49mmol/L, pyruvic 0,39mmol/L; lactate/pyruvate ratio 14.08; beta-hydroxybutyrate and acetoacetate negative, thiamine monophosphate 95nmol/L, thiamine pyrophosphate and free thiamine undetectable, aminoacids and acylcarnitine negative, coenzyme Q 0,72mumol/L. Genetic research confirmed the diagnosis, indicating thiamine transporter deficiency type2 (hTHTR2) with homozygous mutation in SLC19A3 gene (p.Ser7Ter/p.Ser7Ter). Autosomal recessive on chromosome 2q36.3. Currently the patient is eight-months old, and has moderate psychomotor impairment. Conclusion(s): Although this condition has low prevalence, it should be included in the differential diagnosis of infants with lactic acidosis, episodes of acute encephalopathy and movement disorders. The prompt initiation of treatment and adequate compliance can prevent future episodes, improving life quality and prognosis. The molecular study should be done in all cases since this might amplify the mutations associated with thiamine transport deficiency. It's the first described case with such an early detection.
