471. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71874970
T1  - Severe metabolic alkalosis and respiratory acidosis with hypokalemia
T3  - National Kidney Foundation 2015 Spring Clinical Meetings, NKF SCM15. Dallas, TX United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Dah K.
A1  - Sultan G.
A1  - Ahmad M.
A1  - Abboud H. 
Y1  - 2015//
N2  - Metabolic alkalosis (MA) has an extensive differential diagnosis. Finding the underlying cause can be challenging in cases associated with clandestine behaviors; such as surreptitious vomiting, laxative and diuretic abuse and long-term use of alkalis. We present a case of severe MA and hypokalemia in a patient with extremely low food/salt intake and Alka-Seltzer ingestion to relieve dyspepsia after gastric surgery. A 73-year-old male presented to the ED with two weeks of generalized weakness. Six months prior, he had partial gastrectomy and distal esophagectomy for gastric adenocarcinoma. He reported marked decrease in food intake and a 50-60 lb weight loss since surgery. No nausea or vomiting. Prescribed medications included aspirin, pantoprazole, metoclopramide, diphenhydramine and hydrocodone/acetaminophen. No diuretics or laxatives. Physical exam: elderly cachectic male with BP 132/77, dry oral mucosa but otherwise normal. Serum studies: sodium 136 mmol/L, potassium 1.7 mmol/L, chloride 75 mmol/L, total carbon dioxide > 49 mmol/L, BUN 6 mg/dL, creatinine 0.57 mg/dL. Venous blood gas: pH 7.37, pCO2 96.3 mmHg, HCO3 54.5 mEq/L. Urine studies (obtained after administration of potassium chloride 50 meq and 1 L 0.9% normal saline): pH 8, sodium 95 mmol/L, potassium 12.3 mmol/L, chloride 39 mmol/L, Urine AG 68. Hypokalemia resolved with potassium chloride. After detailed discussion the patient reported ingesting at least 10 tablets/day (230 meq sodium bicarbonate/day) of generic Alka-Seltzer for the past 3 months to relieve dyspepsia. High urine pH and AG support the diagnosis of MA secondary to bicarbonate ingestion. This case illustrates both the generation and maintenance phases of MA in the setting of normal renal function due to excess bicarbonate ingestion and extremely low food/salt intake. The persistent bicarbonate load increased potassium excretion and the resulting profound hypokalemia likely contributed to chloride losses. The hypokalemia coupled with the hypochloremia maintained the MA. The respiratory acidosis is likely secondary to hypokalemia-induced respiratory muscle paralysis.
