503. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72042115
T1  - Home high-flow nasal cannulae as a treatment for tracheomalacia
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2014. San Diego, CA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Nguyen T.
A1  - Laberge S.
A1  - Lapierre G. 
Y1  - 2014//
N2  - Severe tracheomalacia is a life threatening condition whose management is challenging. Here we describe a case of tracheomalacia treated with long term high-flow cannula. A 39-week gestational age infant was noted to have thick secretions, stridor and difficulty breathing at birth. Orogastric tube insertion was unsuccessful and a subsequent chest x-ray was suggestive of esophageal atresia. The patient was rapidly scheduled for surgery at 1 day of life. Preoperative bronchoscopy revealed severe tracheomalacia with bulging of the posterior membranous tracheal wall causing more than 50% obstruction of the trachea. Esophageal atresia type C was confirmed upon surgery. Ligation of the fistula and end to end oesophagus anastomosis were performed without complication. He was rapidly extubated within 24h and maintained with Bipap. Weaning of positive pressure caused increased respiratory distress and was stopped. Recurrent regurgitation with nasogastric feeding and failure to thrive were observed the next weeks. A barium swallow and impedancemetry revealed oesophageal dysmotility and severe gastro-esophageal reflux (GERD) respectively. The patient underwent first a gastrostomy at day 20, followed by a Nissen fundoplicature a few weeks later as GERD symptoms persisted. At 2 months, he was switched to high-flow nasal cannulae at 5LPM with ambient air. During the ensuing months, attempts to wean high-flow nasal cannula failed, with increased stridor, SaO2<90% and PCO2>65 mmHg. A previous chest CT scan had shown the absence of vascular ring. Bronchoscopy was repeated at 4 months, which demonstrated left main bronchus malacia in addition to severe tracheomalacia with involvement of the cervical trachea to the carina. The weight gain was satisfying over the next month and the patient remained stable with continuous high-flow nasal cannula. The patient was discharged at 5 months with the AIRVOTM 2 humidifier with integrated flow generator at a flow of 5 LPM and ambient air. At discharge, prolonged pulse oxymetry had shown mean SaO2 of 97% and the patient had a PCO2 of 53 mmHg. As the patient continued to evolve well at 9 months, high-flow nasal cannula was discontinued during waking hours and finally stopped at the age of 1 year. So far, we have used long term home high-flow nasal cannula in three patients with severe tracheomalacia and no adverse event had been identified. Aortopexy, tracheostomy and tracheal reconstruction are the established treatments for tracheomalacia, with variable results and complications reported. This is the first report of successful treatment of tracheomalacia using this novel treatment.
