505. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71801874
T1  - Nutritional counseling significantly improves metabolic variables in overweight/obese women with polycystic ovary syndrome
T3  - 36th European Society for Clinical Nutrition and Metabolism, ESPEN Congress. Geneva Switzerland.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Nybacka A.
A1  - Hellstrom P.M.
A1  - Hirachberg A.L. 
Y1  - 2014//
N2  - Rationale: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is the most common endocrine disorder in women of fertile age with a prevalence estimated to 5 10%. Obesity affects over 50% of women with PCOS. Both non-obese and obese PCOS phenotypes are prone to increase waist to hip ratio, develop insulin resistance and dyslipidemia. In this study, we evaluated the effects of dietary change as part of life-style interventions on BMI, body composition, blood lipids and markers of insulin resistance in overweight/obese women with PCOS. Method(s): 57 PCOS women were included with BMI >27, 18 40 years of age and oligo/-amenorrhea. Women were randomly assigned to three groups: Diet (D, n=19), exercise (E, n =19) and diet plus exercise (DE, n=19). The D groups received individual nutritional counseling by a senior dietician and were recommended a balanced diet, and to reduce the energy level with at least 700 kcal. The E group received exercise advice from a physiotherapist on an ambulatory regimen. Food intake was assessed by self-reporting 24 hours recall during 4 days before and at the end of intervention. Determination of BMI, waist/hip ratio, blood pressure, body composition (DXA), and oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) were performed at baseline and after 16 weeks of intervention. Result(s): BMI, waist circumference and total cholesterol were significantly reduced in the D and DE groups, as well as LDL and HOMA index in the D group. In the E group, there was a smaller decrease in BMI and waist circumference. The strongest predictor of reduced BMI was an increase in fiber intake ( 0.33, p<0.05), whereas a decrease in trans fatty acids predicted a decrease in insulinogenic index (0.50, p< 0.01). Conclusion(s): Individual nutritional counseling leading to increased fiber intake and reduced intake of trans fatty acids can significantly improve metabolic disturbances in overweight/obese women with PCOS.
