514. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71559359
T1  - Short-term intervention with liraglutide improved eating behavior in obese women with polycystic ovary syndrome
T3  - 74th Scientific Sessions of the American Diabetes Association. San Francisco, CA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Sever M.J.
A1  - Kravos N.
A1  - Janez A. 
Y1  - 2014//
N2  - Objective: Eating behavior may influence metabolic and hormonal pattern in polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). Glucagon-like peptide 1 receptor agonists (GLP-1 RA) stimulate satiety leading to reductions in food intake and body weight. The effects of GLP-1 RA liraglutide on eating behavior of women with PCOS have not been investigated yet. Method(s): 36 obese women with PCOS (mean+/-SD, aged 31.2 +/-7.8 years, with BMI 38. 7+/- 0.1 kg/m2), pretreated with metformin (1000 mg BID) were switched to liraglutide 1.2 mg QD sc for 12 weeks. No additional lifestyle intervention was allowed. Body weight were examined at baseline and after 12 weeks. Eating behavior was assessed at baseline and at study end by Eating Questionnaire (TFEQ-R18), measuring three different aspects of eating behavior: restrained (conscious restriction of food intake in order to control body weight or to promote weight loss) , uncontrolled (tendency to eat more than usual due to a loss of control over intake accompanied by subjective feelings of hunger), and emotional eating (inability to resist emotional cues). Result(s): Subjects treated with liraglutide lost on average of 3.8+/-0.1 kg (p<0.001). In addition, significant reductions of waist circumference (p<0.001) and visceral adipose tissue (VAT) mass, volume and area as assessed by DXA were demonstrated from baseline to the end of the study (p<0.001 and p=0.003, p=0.003 and p=0.003, respectively). TFEQ-R18 scores were significantly different pre- and post liraglutide intervention. After treatment with liraglutide the uncontrolled eating (UE) score decreased from 36,8 +/- 24,5 to 19,6 +/- 18,4 scores (p<0.001) and emotional eating (EE) decreased from 49,9 +/- 33,3 to 28,5 +/- 26,9 scores (p<0.001). Scores for cognitive restraint (CR) were not changed. EE were significantly correlated with weight loss (r = 0.344, P = 0.040). Conclusion(s): Short-term liraglutide treatment was associated with weight loss and significantly improved eating behavior in obese women with PCOS.
