A1  - Cote G.A. 
Y1  - 2014//
N2  - Severe acute pancreatitis is one of the most catabolic illnesses, with high nutritional requirements. Several clinical trials and their meta-analysis have shown that enteral nutrition is superior to parenteral, but it is unclear whether enteral feeding avoiding pancreatic stimulation by distal jejunal (>40cm past the ligament of Treitz) feeding tube placement (NGJ) is better than simple nasogastric feeding (NG). To investigate this, a 4-week multicenter study was conducted restricting enrollment to those with objective evidence of severe disease (abdominal pain with >x3 increase in serum amylase or lipase, plus multiple organ failure resistant to early aggressive IV fluid resuscitation as defined by a Marshall score of >=2, or persistent systemic inflammatory response with two or more features of (1) temperature > 38degree C or < 36degree C; (2) HR > 90 BPM; (3) RR > 20 / min; (4) WBC > 12,000 or (5) pCO2 < 32 mmHg, documented at least twice over a period of > 24 hours, or pancreatic necrosis >30%, or CT severity index >8, or APACHE II score >8, or a Ranson's score >3). Only patients with the first onset of abdominal pain within 96h were eligible initially. Statistical power calculations based on differences feeding tolerance, which indicated the need to randomize 135 patients. 196 patients were screened, but only 26 were randomized over a 5 year period, 12 to NG feeding and 14 to NGJ (the study was then stopped). Feeding was started at 25cc/h for the first 24h, then increased with tolerance to 50cc/h for 24h then goal; a semi-elemental formula was used. Result(s): 'Feeding failure' defined as failure to achieve a feeding rate of >10% of goal for a 48h period occurred in 0/14 NGJ patients and in 6/11 NG patients (primarily due to nausea, vomiting, or GRVs >500ml/4h), necessitating crossover to NGJ. As a result, the quantity of feed delivered was significantly higher in NGJ patients (Table). Serious adverse events (cardiorespiratory arrests) occurred in 2 NGJ and no NG patients; 2 NGJ patients died of progressive organ failure and compartment syndrome. In conclusion, this preliminary analysis shows that NGJ feeding was more effective in providing enteral feeding than NG feeding, but there were insufficient numbers enrolled to determine whether this translated into better outcome. The high ineligibility rate encountered highlights the difficulties in conducting RCTs in this heterogeneous population of critically ill patients, with complex etiology and co-morbid conditions. (Figure Presented).
