520. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71438340
T1  - A low insulinemic diet improves binge eating and quality-of-life in women with pcos
T3  - 22nd Annual Congress on Women's Health 2014. Washington, DC United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Berenson A.
A1  - Pohlmeier A.
A1  - Phy J.
A1  - Boylan M.
A1  - Cooper J.
A1  - Spallholz J.
A1  - Harris K. 
Y1  - 2014//
N2  - Background: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) affects approximately 5 million women of reproductive age in the United States and is associated with increased risk of obesity, which often leads to disordered eating behaviors and reduced quality of life. Women with PCOS typically have hyperinsulinemia and hyperandrogenemia, which have been shown to be associated with abnormal eating behaviors. Research shows that carbohydrates from dairy and starch-based foods have greater insulinemic properties than carbohydrates from non-starchy vegetables and fruits. Objective(s): The purpose of this study was to determine whether an 8-week dietary intervention eliminating insulinemic foods reduces binge eating using the Binge Eating Scale (BES) and quality of life using the PCOS-specific Quality of Life Questionnaire (PCOSQ). Material/Methods: Twenty four women with PCOS between 18-45 years (BMI = 25 kg/m2 and = 45 kg/m2) completed an 8-week dietary intervention eliminating dairy and starchbased foods due to their insulinemic properties. Women were allowed to consume lean protein, non-starchy vegetables and fruits, nuts and seeds in ad libitum amounts. Diagnosis of PCOS was based on oligo- and/or amenorrhea, presence of hyperandrogenism, and/or presence of polycystic ovaries determined by ultrasound. Result(s): There was a significant reduction in the BES score from 18.0 +/- 7.4 to 7.0 +/- 4.6 (p < 0.0001). All domains on the PCOSQ were significantly improved: emotions (p < 0.0001), hair growth (p = 0.002), body weight (p < 0.0001), infertility (p < 0.0001), and menstruation (p < 0.0001). Conclusion(s): Binge eating scores and health-related qualityof- life scores were all significantly improved after an 8-week low insulinemic dietary intervention in women with PCOS.
