524. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71019026
T1  - Progression and remission of Type 2 diabetes and all aspects of the metabolic syndrome in a sibling pair with Alstrom syndrome
T3  - Diabetes UK Professional Conference 2013. Manchester United Kingdom.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Paisey R.B.
A1  - Geberhiwot T.
A1  - Waterson M.
A1  - Costelloe M.
A1  - Bunce S.
A1  - Cramb R.
A1  - Parkinson K. 
Y1  - 2013//
N2  - Aims: The syndromic diabetes of Alstrom syndrome is an extreme paradigm for insulin resistant diabetes. We report the effects of lifestyle changes on diabetes, hypertension, hypertriglyceridaemia, hyperinsulinaemia and hepatic fibrosis in two Alstrom siblings. Method(s): Patient 1, a 24 year old male, had developed Type 2 diabetes one year previously with hypertension and dyslipidaemia. Physical and metabolic changes were studied before and after an increase in exercise including 1-2h walking daily and reduction of dietary fat and sugar over one year. Patient 2, his 21 year old sister, had maintained normal glucose tolerance but over the same time period developed low mood, stopped exercising and substantially increased food intake. She underwent similar investigations. Result(s): Patient 1 experienced the following changes: weight decreased from 76.3 to 71kg accompanied by reductions in blood pressure 130/80 to 110/72mm Hg, HbA1c 57 to 34mmol/mol, serum triglycerides 3.2 to 1.8mmol/l, postprandial C-peptide 12346 to 6520pmol/l, and serum enhanced liver fibrosis test 9.1 to 8.3. In contrast over the same time period patient 2 increased weight from 69 to 74kg, blood pressure from 120/75 to 142/90mm Hg, HbA1c from 36 to 58mmol/mol, serum triglycerides from 2.1 to 4.3mmol/l, serum C-peptide 6918 to 8838pmol/l and ELF test from 8.1 to 9.4. She also developed polycystic ovarian syndrome. Conclusion(s): All of the features of the metabolic syndrome respond strikingly to lifestyle changes in Alstrom syndrome offering hope for treatment and potential insight into insulin resistance in the wider population.
