560. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71463264
T1  - A boy with renal magnesium wasting, central hyperventilation, feeding difficulties and suspected mitochondrial disease
T3  - 44. Wissenschaftliche Jahrestagung der Gesellschaft fur Padiatrische Nephrologie, GPN. Munster Germany.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Koemhoff M.
A1  - Spronsen F. 
Y1  - 2013//
N2  - Case report: The male patient is the first child of healthy non-consanguineous parents born after an uncomplicated pregnancy. In late infancy he started to drink poorly. He presented at 21 months of age with difficulties to eat and drink and poor weight gain. A developmental delay was not noted. Blood analysis: electrolytes (mmol/l): Na: 133, K: 2,7, Cl 94, PO4; 1,2, Mg: 0,46; increased plasma renin activity and aldosterone. pH; 7,4, pCO2: 5,1, HCO3: 23. Renal fractional excretion of all minerals except calcium was initially elevated and required oral substitution. Aminoaciduria, glucosuria or enhanced excretion of s2-microglublin were absent. In contrast to magnesium, which is still supplemented, the remaining electrolytes are normal with regular intake. Additional biochemical and clinical features include elevated liver enzymes & creatine kinase and hepatomegaly, respectively. A persistently low pCO2 (venous sampling, mean 3,5 +/- 1 kPa, reference range: 5,5-6,8) and an increased respiration rate (25/min) suggested central hyperventilation. Other causes of hyperventilation were excluded (pontine glioma, methemoglobinemia, cyanide poisoning or pulmonary disease). Metabolic workup suggests mitochondrial disease with increased fasting alanine levels, moderately increased lactate levels in blood and increased urinary lactate/creatinine ratios. Analysis of mitochondrial DNA from blood leucocytes and a HD-DGH microarray were both normal. Genetic analysis for MNGIE (mitochondrial neurogastrointestinal encephalopathy) is pending as are results of muscle and kidney biopsy. Conclusion(s): We described a male patient with renal magnesium wasting next to other peculiar features and biochemical abnormalities consistent with mitochondrial disease.
