T1  - Polycystic ovary syndrome
T3  - 20th Annual Meeting of the Society for Free Radical Biology and Medicine, SFRBM's 2013. San Antonio, TX United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Nusrat O. 
Y1  - 2013//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a common endocrinopathy in women of reproductive age (12-45 years old), with a prevalence of 5-10%. There are many diagnostic criteria, and in general it centers on the features of hyperandrogenism and/or hyperandrogenemia (acne, masculinization), oligo-ovulation and polycystic ovarian morphology and these features vary between women. and in a majority of cases insulin resistance is present (the causes still unknown), with compensatory hyperinsulinemia with hyperandrogenism via stimulation of ovarian androgen secretion and inhibition of hepatic sex hormone-binding globulin production. in women with PCOS it is observed that there is adipose tissue dysfunction with insulin resistance and obesity. Also there are other factors such as environmental and genetic factors that can play a potential role in the development of PCOS. This syndrome is associated with much morbidity, including infertility, obstetrical complications, type 2 diabetes mellitus, cardiovascular disease, mood and eating disorders. the diagnosis of PCOS hinges on establishing key features while ruling out other hyperandrogenic or oligo-ovulatory disorders. 2 Treatment goals are focused to ameliorating hyperandrogenic symptoms that mediated by reactive oxygen species, inducing ovulation and preventing cardiometabolic complications.
