565. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71198785
T1  - Metabolic and behavioral effects of bariatric surgery on a rat model of polycystic ovary syndrome
T3  - 60th Annual Scientific Meeting of the Society for Gynecologic Investigation, SGI 2013. Orlando, FL United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Ressler I.B.
A1  - Grayson B.E.
A1  - Seeley. R.J. 
Y1  - 2013//
N2  - Objective: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is the most common endocrine disorder affecting women of reproductive age. Its clinical expression is diverse, including gynecologic, metabolic and behavioral effects, with many affected by obesity and decreased quality of life. Our objective was to investigate the impact of vertical sleeve gastrectomy (VSG), a commonly used bariatric procedure, on the metabolic and behavioral health of a rat model of PCOS. Design(s): Preclinical rodent basic research. Material(s) and Method(s): Female Long Evans rats were implanted with the nonaromatizable androgen dihydrotestosterone (DHT) (n=23) or placebo (n=23) pellets starting before puberty. Animals were maintained on a high-fat diet (HFD) (40% butter fat calories) ad libitum. Animals received either sham surgery (SHAM) or VSG. Behavioral measures included the elevated plus maze and corticosterone levels. Data were analyzed by Student's t-test or the appropriate ANOVA. Result(s): Plasma DHT significantly increased 3-fold in those implanted with the DHT pellet (123.9+/-10.1 vs. 37.1+/-5.4 ng/mL, p<0.0001). DHT-treated rats had irregular cycles, increased food intake, increased body weight, greater fat mass and higher fasting glucose levels (116.0+/-1.2 vs. 109.9+/-1.8 mg/dL, p=0.007). DHT-treated rats demonstrated increased anxiety-like behavior in the elevated plus maze. VSG caused loss of body weight and body fat, as well as improved fasting glucose (102.8+/-1.6 vs. 110.9+/-2.2 mg/dL, p=0.007) and triglyceride levels (75.97+/-6.3 vs. 156.3+/-21.3 mg/dL, p=0.001) in DHT-treated rats. After a mild stressor, corticosterone levels were lower in all VSG animals as compared to SHAM. Conclusion(s): Bariatric surgery improves obesity and metabolic abnormalities in a PCOS rat model. In addition, our results show an increase in anxietyrelated behavior in this model, suggesting an organic cause of altered anxiety levels related to hyperandrogenism. Bariatric surgery may improve this stress phenotype as suggested by lowering corticosterone levels. Further research is needed to clarify the mechanism of androgens affecting female behavior.
