569. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71164979
T1  - Relationship between postprandial grelin and insulin blood levels in obese women with and without polycystic ovary syndrome
T3  - International Federation of Fertility Societies 21st World Congress on Fertility and Sterility and the 69th Annual Meeting of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine, IFFS-ASRM 2013. Boston, MA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Silva-de-Sa M.F.
A1  - Cremonezi C.C.
A1  - Penaforte F.R.O.
A1  - Diez-Garcia R.W. 
Y1  - 2013//
N2  - OBJECTIVE:Women with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) are predisposed to insulin resistance (IR) and obesity. Imbalance on ghrelin secretion for appetite regulation may be involved. We have compared postprandial ghrelin and insulin responses to an ad libitum meal between obese women with and those without PCOS. DESIGN: Intervention study. MATERIALS AND METHODS: We assessed 30 obese women with PCOS and 23 obese women without PCOS. Blood samples were taken under fasting conditions, preprandially and 15, 45, 75 and 135 min after the beginning of an ad libitum meal, and ghrelin, insulin and glucose concentrations were analyzed. IR was classified using basal insulin and the HOMA index. RESULT(S): Mean food intake by obese women with and without PCOS was similar (468 +/- 150 g vs 444 +/- 165 g, P = 0.60). IR was found in 56,6% in PCOS group compared with 30,4% in control (p<0,01). There were significant negative correlation between fasting ghrelin and HOMAR (r= 0.6787; p= 0.0004) only in control group. The postprandial ghrelin and insulin responses were similar in obese women with PCOS and those without PCOS. There was a significant negative correlation between ghrelin and insulin concentrations in both groups, control (r=-0,4512; p<0,0001) and PCOS (r=-0,3110; p<0,0001). However, when the subjects were separated according to IR, there was a significant negative correlation in women without (r=-0.34; P < 0.0001), but not with IR (r=-0.15; P = 0.07). The area under the curve for ghrelin was greater in non IR group (p<0,01). CONCLUSION(S): The imbalance in the feedback mechanisms between insulin and ghrelin present in obese women with or without PCOS seems to be more related to the IR than PCOS itself. This finding suggests that the long exposition to IR observed in obese patients may affect the gastric cells function, inducing to an impairment of ghrelin suppression by insulin.
