570. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71164923
T1  - Evaluation of hunger sensation, ad libitum food intake, and ghrelin postprandial response in obese women with and without polycystic ovary syndrome
T3  - International Federation of Fertility Societies 21st World Congress on Fertility and Sterility and the 69th Annual Meeting of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine, IFFS-ASRM 2013. Boston, MA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Silva-de-Sa M.F.
A1  - Japur C.C.
A1  - Penaforte F.R.O.
A1  - Diez-Garcia R.W. 
Y1  - 2013//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: We hypothesized that obese women with Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) should present higher pre-prandial hunger and larger ad libitum food intake as well as lower post-prandial ghrelin suppression compared with obese women without PCOS (Control). Therefore, this study aimed to evaluate hunger sensation, ad libitum food intake, and ghrelin post-prandial response in obese women with and without PCOS. DESIGN: Intervention study. MATERIALS AND METHODS: This study included 53 obese women, 30 of which had SOP and 23 of which were Control. For characterization of the sample, we assessed anthropometric, and body composition data; and usual food intake. The ad libitum food intake was quantified by weighing the pan before and after the meal. Hunger sensation was evaluated by means of 100-mm analogical subjective scales in the pre- (0 min) and postprandial periods (15, 45, 75, and 135 min after the start of the meal). Ghrelin, insulin, and glucose were analyzed at these same times. Ad libitum and usual food intake was analyzed using a linear regression model adjusted by body mass index; hormone and glucose analysis was carried out using a mixed-effects linear model. P-value < 0.05 was considered significant. RESULT(S): Women with PCOS did not present higher hunger sensation (PCOS: 59 +/- 26mm x Control: 51 +/- 32mm; p=0.40) or larger ad libitum food intake (615 +/- 197kcal x 583 +/- 217kcal; p=0.60). Ghrelin, insulin, and glucose values in the pre- and postprandial periods were also similar in the two groups. The PCOS group presented faster return of hunger sensation (1 h after the meal) and larger usual food intake (2502 +/- 656kcal x 2102 +/- 665kcal; p=0.04). The SOP group presented higher insulin resistance (56.6% x 30.4%; p<0.01). CONCLUSION(S): From analysis of the ghrelin behavior, it was possible to conclude that neither its pre-prandial levels nor the variation taking place before and after the meal are determinants of food intake in obese women with or without PCOS.
