591. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71113615
T1  - x00EC;Losing weight, gaining fertilityi: A multidisciplinary lifestyle program for overweight women with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), a study protocol
T3  - 28th Annual Meeting of the European Society of Human Reproduction and Embryology, ESHRE 2012. Istanbul Turkey.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Jiskoot L.G.
A1  - De Niet J.E.
A1  - Van Busschbach J.J.
A1  - Van Stigt V.W.H.C.
A1  - Van Egmond A.M.E.
A1  - Verbiest A.C.M.
A1  - Nugteren S.
A1  - De Klerk C.
A1  - Laven J.S.E. 
Y1  - 2012//
N2  - Introduction: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a common endocrine disturbance that affects 5-10% of women in their reproductive years. Being overweight and gaining weight worsens reproductive, metabolic and psychological features of PCOS. Losing as little as 5 to 10% of the initial body weight improves all clinical features and often leads to spontaneous ovulation and pregnancy in women with PCOS. Therefore, the aim of this study is to investigate the effect of a multidisciplinary lifestyle program on body mass index (BMI) as well as on reproductive outcomes in women with PCOS. Material(s) and Method(s): Women aged between 18-38 years with PCOS and a BMI >25 kg/m2 who are referred to the Erasmus MC for fertility problems are asked to participate in the study. A total of 234 patients will be randomized in a 2:1 ratio into an experimental group (n = 156) and a control group (n = 78) according to a computer-generated random numbers table. This study has been registered in the Dutch trial registry (TC 2450). The experimental group receives a twelve-month multidisciplinary cognitive-behavioural lifestyle intervention aimed at sustainable changes in physical activity and eating habits. The intervention is carried out by a multidisciplinary team consisting of a psychologist or social worker, a dietician, a physiotherapist and a gynaecologist. Women attend 20 group sessions in 12 months (duration: 3,5 hours). Additionally, participants receive 5 individual counselling sessions from all professionals. The control group receives treatment as usual which involves individual counselling about health risks for both mother and child. Counselling is provided by the treating physician in 5 meetings. After the first three months, half of the participants (n = 78) in the experimental group receive an additional maintenance intervention via SMS. For nine months participants weekly send self-monitoring information regarding their diet, physical activity and emotions via SMS. A semi-automated software program generates feedback on the incoming messages. These feedback messages are aimed at providing social support, encouraging positive behaviour and empowering behavioural strategies. Outcome variables will be measured at the start of the study, at three, six, nine and twelve months. BMI is the primary outcome. Secondary outcomes include: reproductive outcomes: cycle duration and frequency and spontaneous pregnancies; (2) anthropomorphometric outcomes: waist circumference (WC), hip circumference (HC), and WC/HC ratio; (3) clinical and biochemical PCOS features: hair growth pattern (Ferriman Gallwey score) and endocrine outcomes; (4) psychological outcomes: eating behaviour and disturbances (The Dutch Eating Behaviour Questionnaire and the Eating Disorder Examination Questionnaire), Quality of Life (the Short Form 36 and the Polycystic Ovary Syndrome Questionnaire), depression (Beck Depression Inventory), self-esteem (the Rosenberg Self Esteem Scale), fear of negative appearance (the Fear of Negative Appearance Evaluation Scale ); and (5) physical activity: the International Physical Activity Questionnaire. In the experimental group a maximum bicycle ergometer test is used to determine exercise intensity and fitness progress. The effect of the interventions on the outcome variables will be determined using mixed modelling. Result(s): This study is currently carried out. Preliminary results of 50 participants will be presented at the meeting. Conclusion(s): We hypothesize that a multidisciplinary cognitive-behavioural lifestyle program leads to a greater sustainable weight loss in women with PCOS and overweight or obesity than usual care. By changing dietary habits and improving physical activity through activating social support and changing behaviours as well as cognitions it is expected that primary and secondary outcomes will improve. This study will show whether a lifestyle program is an effective complement to current invasive fertility treatments in overweight women with PCOS. If so, lifestyle modification should be included in standard care protocols for this particular patient group.
