592. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 71112962
T1  - Eating disorders in an ART population: A Danish national controlled cohort study
T3  - 28th Annual Meeting of the European Society of Human Reproduction and Embryology, ESHRE 2012. Istanbul Turkey.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Assens M.
A1  - Pinborg A.
A1  - Ebdrup N.H.
A1  - Hougaard C.O.
A1  - Hageman I.
A1  - Schmidt L. 
Y1  - 2012//
N2  - Introduction: Eating disorders are known to cause anovulation and amenorrhea and can therefore be the main cause of infertility. Our primary objective was to investigate the prevalence of eating disorders in a national ART (assisted reproductive techniques) cohort and to study the causes of infertility in women with eating disorders receiving ART treatment. We also aimed to explore the relation between the time of diagnosis of an eating disorder and the time of ART treatment. The second objective was to analyze live birth rates and perinatal outcomes among women with an eating disorder compared to the general ART population. Material(s) and Method(s): Data from the national Danish IVF-register 1.1.1994 - 30.9.2009 on all women having received ART treatment were linked with national data from the Medical Birth Register and the Psychiatric Central Research Register for a diagnosis of eating disorder. In total 42915 women (the National ART Cohort) had received ART treatment, and of these 271 (0.6%) were diagnosed with an eating disorder. Descriptive comparisons between women in the ART population with and without an eating disorder were performed with chi-square tests and t-tests. Result(s): Of the 271 women with an eating disorder in the National ART Cohort, 226 (83.4%) were diagnosed with an eating disorder prior to ART treatment, 5 (1.8%) during, and 40 (14.8%) after ART treatment. In this study we focused on the women, who were diagnosed with an eating disorder prior to ART treatment. The mean age at first eating disorder diagnosis was 23.4 (+/-5.5) and the mean time between last eating disorder diagnosis and ART enrollment was 6.8 years (+/-4.1). At time of referral to ART treatment women with an eating disorder were significantly younger 31.0 (+/-4.8) than the rest of the National ART Cohort 33.0 (+/-4.5) (P < 0.001). Ovulatory disorders were significantly more frequent as the main cause of infertility 31 (16.2%) vs. 2018 (5.6%) in women with eating disorders vs. the ART population in general (P < 0.001). The mean number of initiated ART cycles was 2.83 (+/-2.12) vs. 3.21 (+/-2.30) in the eating disorder group vs. the comparison group (P = 0.008). Among women diagnosed with an eating disorder before ART treatment 180 (79.6%) achieved a live birth compared to the general ART-population where 30302 (71.0%, P = 0.675) achieved a live birth. The mean birth weight of ART singletons born to mothers with an eating disorder was 3384 grams (+/-628), which did not differ significantly from the comparison group; 3407 grams (+/-633). Likewise the difference in mean gestational age was 275.4 days (+/-13.55) vs. 276.2 days (+/-15.52). More ART singletons born to mothers with an eating disorder had low birth weight (<2500 gram) (14 (11.4%) vs. 1341 (6.8%)) Conclusion(s): This study confirms that women with an eating disorder also receive ART-treatment. However, half of these women had their last eating disorder diagnosis almost seven years prior to their ART treatment. The significantly higher number of ovulation pathology in the study population may indicate that some of the ART women still suffer from an active eating disorder. In general reassuring perinatal outcomes were found for ART singletons born to women with eating disorders although we cannot decline that this is partly explained by the fact that women with an eating disorder experience partial relief from their thoughts about food during pregnancy and take up a more normal eating pattern to avoid causing any harm to their child.
