AN  - 71066355
T1  - Methemoglobinemia: Another "great masquerader?"
T3  - 42nd Critical Care Congress of the Society of Critical Care Medicine, SCCM 2013. San Juan Puerto Rico.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Wheeler J.
A1  - Allareddy V.
A1  - Lidsky K. 
Y1  - 2012//
N2  - Case Reports: Background:Methemoglobinemia(mHb), whether congenital or acquired, refers to an altered state of Hb in which the ferrous ions of heme moi ety are oxidized to ferric state decreasing its ability to bind oxygen. We report an unusual case of mHb in an infant with Down syndrome & congenital heart disease(CHD). Clinical history, "saturation gap", & poor response to Positive Pressure Ventilation(PPV) are major clues to the diagnosis. However, high index of suspicion is still warranted in pt's with UNEXPLAINED persistent hypoxia & cyanosis especially in the setting of CHD. Dehydration has been associated with mHb. Persistent mHb greater than 40% is associated with significant morbidity & mortality. Case: 5 wk old male with CHD & Down Syndrome presented with progressive listlessness, increased WOB, poor feeding & diarrhea(1-2 days). Pt appeared pale, dusky & minimally responsive with sinus tachycardia, hypotension & moderate to severe dehydration. Initial pulse ox 85% on RA was attributed to bidirectional VSD. Gas: pH <6.8, pCo2 34, paO2 140, HCo3 < 5, BE neg 28, elevated lactate. Pt intubated/PPV for altered mental status & worsening hemodynamics(needing fluid & vasoactive support). Significant labs: WBC 31k, 33% bands, Hb 11.6; significantly elevated pro-T BNP(53 k), LFT's, BUN, and ammonia; with hyponatremia(130) and hyperchloremia. EKG:Prolonged QTc, ECHO: bidirectional large VSD, ASD, PDA with good function on vasoactive support. Pt continued to be cyanotic. Blood was chocolate brown color. COOXIMETRY: Initial mHb 60%, Carboxy Hb 1.6%. Treatment with one dose of Methylene blue led to complete resolution of hypoxia & cyanosis within a few hours-with mHB less than 5. Pt was successfully weaned off vasoactive agents, & extubated 4d later with normal hemodynamics, labs, & discharged home. Extensive work up for mHb, including Cytochrome b5 reductase were normal. ID work up was negative. Conclusion(s): mHB should be an important differential in the work up of unexplained, persistent hypoxia & cyanosis. Though, saturation gap, history & poor response to PPV are major clues to the diagnosis, Cooximetry remains the practical diagnostic test of choice in suspected cases.
