T1  - Breast-feeding is affected in women with history of chronic anovulation
T3  - 20th FIGO World Congress of Gynecology and Obstetrics. Rome Italy.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Elfaissal Y.M.
A1  - Serour A.G. 
Y1  - 2012//
N2  - Objectives: To describe the menstrual patterns occurring in fully breast-feeding women with a well documented history of chronic anovulation during the first months postpartum, and to compare the findings to women with regular menstrual cycles, during the same period of time. Materials: Two groups of women were observed during the period of first six months postpartum. Voluntary participants were selected based on their wish not to use any hormonal contraceptives initially. The first group included 100 women with the history of being chronically anovulatory and in whom conception was assisted by induction of ovulation and/or ART. The second group included 100 women with regular menses and fertility prior to conception. Method(s): Participants were instructed to take descriptive records of the uterine bleeding episodes (after cessation of lochia), using a diary form. They were also asked to report at any time if they seek treatment for their current menstrual patterns. Data from the menstrual diaries were collected and analyzed. Result(s): The mean number of amenorrhea days in the first group was 48.67 days and 95.18 days in the second. Regular menses, amenorrhea, oligomenorrhea, menorrhagia and metrorrhagia were encountered in 0, 13 (13.4%), 32 (32.9%), 0 and 52 (53.6%) participants of the first group, respectively and in 24 (25.5%), 49 (52.1%), 4 (4.2%), 8 (8.5%) and 9 (9.6%) participants of the second group, respectively. 51 (52.6%) participants of the first group requested treatment for their menstrual pattern, in face of 9 of the second group. Of the first group, only 13 (13.4%) reported satisfaction of their status, in comparison to 71 (75.5%) of the 2nd group. The net result was abandonment of lactation in 48 (49.5%) and 5 (5.3%) of the 1st and 2nd group respectively. Conclusion(s): Lactation amenorrhea is of shorter duration in lactating women with a history of chronic anovulation; with the commonest bleeding pattern being metrorrhagia. These findings significantly altered the lifestyle of this group of women, with a consequent request of treatment, resulting eventually in stopping lactation.
