602. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70833248
T1  - Breast size increment during pregnancy and breast feeding in PCOS mothers: A follow-up study of a randomized controlled trial on metformin vs. placebo
T3  - 94th Annual Meeting and Expo of the Endocrine Society, ENDO 2012. Houston, TX United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Vanky E.
A1  - Nordskar J.
A1  - Leithe H.
A1  - Hjorth-Hansen A.
A1  - Martinussen M.P.
A1  - Carlsen S.M. 
Y1  - 2012//
N2  - Background: The significance of breast size increment in PCOS women during pregnancy, and the impact of metformin on breast feeding duration are essentially unexplored. Objective(s): To study breast size increment in pregnancy and the impact of metformin during pregnancy on breast feeding in women with PCOS. Design(s): A follow-up study of a randomized controlled multicentre trial (The PregMet study). Intervention(s): Women with PCOS were randomized to metformin or placebo from first trimester to delivery. Questionnaires were sent to 256 participants one year postpartum, 199 responded. Main Outcome Measure(s): Pre-pregnancy and late pregnancy bra size, breast feeding pattern were registered and androgen levels measured in the mothers. Result(s): No difference in breast size increment and breast feeding were found between the placebo and metformin group. Breast size increment during pregnancy correlated positively to the duration of exclusive breastfeeding, while BMI correlated negatively to the duration of partial breast feeding. Dehydroepiandrosterone-sulfate (DHEAS), testosterone and free testosterone index (FTI) in pregnancy did not correlate to breast size increment or duration of breast feeding. Women with no change in breast size were older, more obese, had higher blood pressure, serum triglycerides and fasting insulin levels, and had shorter duration of breast feeding compared to those with breast size increment. Conclusion s: PCOS women with no breast size increment in pregnancy seem to be more metabolically disturbed and less able to breast feed. Metformin supplementation during pregnancy did not improve their capability to breast feed.
