615. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70680294
T1  - Glucagon-like peptide-1 increases brain FMRI activity in rats
T3  - 29th Annual Scientific Meeting of the Obesity Society, Obesity 2011. Orlando, FL United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Min D.K.
A1  - Tuor U.I.
A1  - Chelikani P.K. 
Y1  - 2011//
N2  - Background: The gut hormone glucagon-like peptide -1 (GLP-1) has been shown to decrease food intake in both rodents and humans. The hypothalamic and brain stem networks are hypothesized to play an important role in the anorexic effects of GLP-1; the role of higher brain centers remains largely unknown. We applied Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging (fMRI) to characterize the spatio-temporal changes in the rat brain in response to intravenous (IV) infusion of GLP-1. Method(s): In feeding experiments, the effects of IV infusion of GLP-1 at 0 or 20 pmol/ kg/min (n=12) on intake of a mixed nutrient liquid meal (Ensure) was determined in overnight food deprived rats. In imaging experiments, brain images were acquired with a 9.4T magnet during IV infusion of GLP-1 at 0 or 20 pmol/kg/min (n=8) in anesthetized rats with continuous monitoring of blood parameters. Result(s): IV infusion of GLP-1 inhibited intake of the mixed nutrient meal by about 25%. GLP-1 infusions produced a significant increase in fMRI activity with 4% of the total voxels in the hypothalamus and nucleus tractus solitarius (NTS), and 7% of the voxels in the hippocampus, correlating to an increase in the fMRI signal intensity. The fMRI activity in the cortex, amygdala and thalamus, and circulating concentrations of pO2, pCO2 and glucose, did not differ between treatments. Conclusion(s): An anorexic dose of systemically administered GLP-1 increased fMRI activity in the hypothalamus, NTS and hippocampus suggesting that these regions may play a role in mediating the inhibitory effects of GLP-1 on food intake.
