621. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70409491
T1  - Controlled feeding experiments demonstrate the impact of diet on the composition of the human gut microbiome
T3  - Digestive Disease Week, DDW 2011. Chicago, IL United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Wu G.D.
A1  - Bewtra M.
A1  - Hoffmann C.
A1  - Chen Y.-Y.
A1  - Keilbaugh S.A.
A1  - Bittinger K.
A1  - Knight R.
A1  - Hwang J.
A1  - Chen J.
A1  - Gilroy E.D.
A1  - Gupta K.
A1  - Nessel L.C.
A1  - Baldassano R.
A1  - Li H.
A1  - Bushman F.D.
A1  - Lewis J.D. 
Y1  - 2011//
N2  - Background: Evidence from rodent models demonstrates that diet influences the gut microbiome composition. Here we examined the ability of dietary composition and caloric intake to influence the human gut microbiome composition. Method(s): Ten healthy volunteers were sequestered and randomly assigned to a high fat-low fiber (HFat, n=5) or low fat-high fiber isocaloric diet (LFat, n=5) for 10 days. Portion sizes were adjusted to fix the dietary fat content. In a second experiment, 6 healthy subjects participated in a crossover trial in which they were fed a high calorie (30% increase from usual) or low calorie (30% decrease from usual) identical diet that differed only in portion size. After a washout period, the participant was assigned to the alternate diet. Fecal samples were collected daily. 454 pyrosequencing of 16S rDNA followed by both weighted (relative abundance) and unweighted (presenceabsence) UniFrac distance measures were used to describe microbiome composition by principal coordinate analysis (PCoA). Mixed effects linear regression was used to assess for changes over time. Result(s): Fecal microbiome composition in Day 1 stool samples was different from samples collected on all other days in both unweighted (p<0.0001) and weighted (p=0.002) UniFrac distance analysis, revealing that the composition of the gut microbiome changed within 24 hours of dietary intervention. This was despite all subjects having retained sitz markers at day 2. We found changes in abundance of the Bacteroidetes phylum in both diet groups (LFat p=0.013, HFat p=0.026 for day 1 vs. all other days). Interestingly, a time-dependent decrease in the Bacteroidetes and increase in Firmicutes over the 10 days of the study (p=0.11 and 0.017) occurred in both the LFat and HFat groups, which differs from results of studies with rodent models. Nevertheless, there was separation between the HFat and LFat groups at day 10 on PCoA2 (weighted UniFrac p=0.032) where PCoA1 mostly captured inter-individual variation. In the second experiment, preliminary data from the first subject demonstrated significant alterations in gut microbiome composition associated with diets that differed in caloric content but not composition. These alterations were also observed within 24-48 hours of dietary intervention. Conclusion(s): The composition of the human gut microbiome responds rapidly to alterations of either dietary composition or caloric intake. Surprisingly, these changes occurred largely before stool had time to move through the gut and, in our first study, the phylum level alterations in the microbiome are different from those reported in rodent model systems. Finally, although highly statistically significant, the data from our first study indicates that the effect of dietary fat and/or fiber on the gut microbiome composition is of modest magnitude relative to intersubject variation.
