651. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70990928
T1  - A qualitative pilot study of long-term care residents' use of nintendo wiiTM
T3  - 2010 Annual Scientific Meeting of the American Geriatrics Society. Orlando, FL United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Brandt K.
A1  - Waldron M.
A1  - Bierman T.
A1  - Malmstrom T.K.
A1  - Paniagua M.A. 
Y1  - 2010//
N2  - The Nintendo Wii is a popular activity at some long-term care facilities.There is little data available about residents' opinions, preferences and motivations for playing Wii.
Purpose:This pilot study surveyed long-term care residents about their use of Wii bowling as a recreational activity. We aimed to characterize appropriate candidates for the game, explore reasons for the game's popularity, and categorize desirable features for other recreational activities.
Methods: Participants (n=11) who played Wii bowling at least once per week for 4 weeks were recruited.Trained interviewers collected data from a self-report questionnaire and the Minimum Data Set. Responses were evaluated based on the number of replies to each item.
Results: Participants reported their overall health as good (mean 3.18 +/- 1.2 on a 5-point scale from 1[Excellent]-5[Poor]).They rated themselves as social (63.6%), happy or very happy (90.9%), not lonely (54.5%), but somewhat bored (63.6%). Most (54.5%) reported spending up to four hours in their rooms or by themselves each day when not asleep. Participants rated Wii bowling as somewhat easy or very easy to learn (81.8%), very enjoyable (60%), and meaningful (50%). They ranked Wii as somewhat exciting or exciting (70%). Most (88.9%) included daily care activities in their strategies to improve or maintain their health. Respondents enjoy organized group (54.5%) and individual activities (63.6%) in their free time. Favorite activities included Wii bowling (62.5%), bingo (75%), and eating (50%). Most enjoy trying new activities (77.8%) and play Wii bowling because they enjoy it (62.5%). Some residents needed assistance with set-up (55.6%) or instruction (44.4%) in order to play. 
Conclusion: Long-term care residents who play Nintendo Wii bowling reported positive experiences overall. Wii bowling was rated as a favorite recreational activity and was chosen for exercise, socializing, nostalgia, and competition. This activity has the potential to engage residents in an otherwise physically-limiting recreational activity, promote social engagement, and provide ease of administration for limited recreational staff.
