652. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70844461
T1  - Rapid breathing in an "Angry" newborn
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2010. New Orleans, LA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Rao D.R.
A1  - Khatwa U.
A1  - Haver K. 
Y1  - 2010//
N2  - A 2 day old term male born at an outside facility was transferred to the neonatal intensive care unit in our institution for evaluation of tachypnea. The pregnancy and vaginal delivery were unremarkable. The birth weight was 3805 grams. Apgars were 9 and 9 at 1 and 5 minutes respectively. Minutes after delivery, the infant's respiratory rate increased to 80 breaths per minute. He was afebrile, and his oxygen saturation was 98% in ambient air. Arterial blood gas analysis revealed a pH of 7.38, pCO2 of 38 and pO2 of 88. His tachypnea resolved within a few minutes only to recur after breastfeeding. During these episodes, the infant had clear breath sounds, mild subcostal retractions and no oxygen desaturation. His mother noticed his respiratory rate increased especially when "angry." Physical exam upon admission to our facility: temperature 36.8degree C, heart rate 162/minute, respiratory rate 40/minute, blood pressure 69/53, weight 3.8 kilograms. Oxygen saturation in ambient air was 98%. The infant was sleeping comfortably. His cardiovascular, abdominal, and neurological examinations were unremarkable. His chest was clear to auscultation with good aeration. Awakening resulted in short audible "sighs" with inspiration followed by rapid abdominal breathing, subcostal retractions and normal exhalation. His electronically monitored respiratory rate climbed to 100 breaths per minute without a decline of his oxygen saturation. When asleep, his respirations normalized. The infant showed no signs of feeding intolerance. Plain films of the chest and abdomen were normal. A polysomnograph revealed diaphragmatic fluttering at a rate of > 400/minute during inspiration superimposed upon a baseline respiratory rate of 40-70/minute. Flexible laryngoscopy demonstrated mild laryngomalacia. Results of polysomnography (Graph presented) Impedance pneumography of the chest and abdomen for a 30 second window demonstrates DF only with inspiration at a rate of greater than 400/min with an underlying respiratory rate of 70 breaths/minute. Diaphragmatic flutter (DF) is a rare condition defined as diaphragmatic contractions at a rate of 35 to 480/min and can occur in all age groups. These contractions typically occur during inspiration, and associated laryngeal collapse with contraction may manifest as stacatto inspiratory noises. Rarely does DF occur during sleep or cause respiratory failure. When DF is associated with dysphagia, laryngomalacia and gastroesophageal reflux, it is known as "respiratory flutter syndrome" (RF). The pathogenesis of DF and RF are unknown, but may involve dysfunction of the respiratory control generators, phrenic neuropathy or direct diaphragmatic irritation. Diagnosis can be made with polysomnography, which in our case revealed fluttering of the respiratory rate during inspiration. DF has been successfully treated with chlorpromazine, a dopamine antagonist, but in other cases, it self-resolves.
