653. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70840520
T1  - Successful use of Airway Pressure Release Ventilation (APRV) in a pregnant patient with severe ARDS
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2010. New Orleans, LA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Jamaleddine G.
A1  - Zein J. 
Y1  - 2010//
N2  - We report the successful use of Airway Pressure Release Ventilation (APRV) on a 25 year old woman who was 30 weeks pregnant with severe ARDS. Case report: A 25 year old woman, 30 weeks pregnant (first pregnancy), presented with cough, fever and dyspnea. She had a history of asthma controlled on inhaled steroids and beta2 agonists. On presentation, she was alert and oriented, in respiratory distress, RR 35, BP 145/80, HR 135, oxygen saturation was 80% on non-rebreather face mask. She had bibasilar crackles and mild expiratory wheezing. She was placed immediately on non invasive positive pressure ventilation (NPPV); ABGaTMs were pH 7.46, PCO2 24 mmHg, PO2 90 mmHg. CBC and chemistry were non remarkable. CXR showed bilateral basilar infiltrates. CT angio ruled out PE and showed bilateral basilar patchy infiltrates. CT chest on presentation (Figure Presented) throughout and there was no distress. Cefatrixone and Azithromycin, steroids, bronchodilators, DVT prophylaxis, and tube feeding were administered. BAL culture was negative; ARDS was due to presumptive viral pneumonitis. The patient was discharged from the hospital and she carried her pregnancy to term without complication. Discussion(s): Management of the pregnant patient with ARDS is very challenging. There is little data on the proper ventilator setting. Use of APRV in our patient was life saving for the mother and the baby. With the present H1N1 pandemic, our findings and experience are of outmost importance. Use of APRV should be considered in all pregnant patients suffering from ARDS.
