800. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 34116270
T1  - Leptin and adiposity
A1  - Ewies A.A.A. 
Y1  - 2001//
N2  - Leptin, secreted almost exclusively by white adipocytes, may serve as a link between fat tissue and the brain. Leptin investigation has increased in many fields, including obesity, anorexia nervosa, diabetes, acquired immune disease, cancer, nephropathy thyroid disease, Cushing's syndrome and growth hormone deficiency. It also appears to have a relationship to some obstetrical and gynaecological conditions, such as puberty, polycystic ovary syndrome, endometriosis, assisted fertility, menopause, foetal growth and pregnancy-induced hypertension. It is widely accepted that leptin, by reducing food intake and increasing thermogenesis, controls body fat tissue and hence body weight. The present review concentrates on the structure, action, regulation of secretion, and the role of leptin in adiposity.
