831. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 28180296
T1  - Leptin and reproduction
A1  - Magoffin D.A.
A1  - Huang C.T.F. 
Y1  - 1998//
N2  - Extremes in body mass, either obesity or anorexia, are associated with anovulation and infertility. Leptin is a recently discovered hormone produced by adipocytes that has been proposed as a metabolic signal to the reproductive system. Circulating leptin concentrations increase in proportion to percent body fat, and there are data to support the concept that leptin plays a role in the onset of puberty. In adults, leptin appears to play a role in promoting hypothalamic function and maintaining adequate levels of gonadotropin secretion. In animal models of leptin deficiency, low extremes of leptin concentrations can impair hypothalamic function, leading to hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. At the other extreme, with leptin concentrations commonly found in obese women, there can be direct suppressive effects on the ovary. High concentrations of leptin appear to impair the sensitivity of the ovarian follicles to FSH stimulation and may contribute to the increased incidence of infertility associated with obesity.
