850. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 25109324
T1  - The masticatory function in DMD patients by video-tape investigations
A1  - Marcello N.
A1  - Ortaggio F.
A1  - Sabadini R. 
Y1  - 1994//
N2  - Chewing and swallowing difficulties can often occur in the later stages of DMD, caused by oromandibular changes with malocclusion and enlargement of the tongue. We studied nine DMD patients, aged between 10-27, by videotape investigations of alimentary behaviour, food intake, masticatory and deglutition functions. Moreover we clinically examined neck, masticatory and tongue muscles and collected Sat 02 and/or pCO2 and pO2 recordings during nocturnal sleep for obstructive apnea detection. From about the age of 13 the patients have difficulty bringing food to mouth with their hands and they can have anterior open bite and large tongue. In four patients with macroglossia, frequent oxygen desaturations were recorded during sleep. All patients had orthodontic problems and an abnormal pattern of masticatory muscular activity was displayed by video-tape analysis because the occlusion was weakened by involvement of jaw-closing muscles. Moreover the mastication was slowing down and lateral movements were increased.
