892. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1980 to 1987>
AN  - 14065316
T1  - Scoliosis and retinal changes in a G syndrome carrier
A1  - Somer M.
A1  - Westerlund A. 
Y1  - 1984//
N2  - The G syndrome is one of the hypertelorism-hypospadias syndromes which is also manifested by stridor and severe feeding problems in infancy. The inheritance is not clear: both X-chromosomal recessive and autosomal dominant inheritance, with male sex limitation, have been suggested. In most families described, one of the parents, usually the mother, shows stigmata of the syndrome. Careful examination of the parents is essential before genetic counselling. We report a patient whose mother shows some findings not reported earlier in carriers of this disorder. The 27-year-old mother shares many of the patient's facial features. She has hypertelorism, a small mouth and micrognathia. Her early history was unremarkable, but at the age of 14 she was operated on because of thoracal scoliosis. At 18 years of age she underwent a partial resection of ovaries because of polycystic changes. Her ophthalmological studies show myopia (-6.75/-8.0 D). Furthermore, lattice degeneration was detected in her peripheral left retina. This was treated by photocoagulation. She has two healthy brothers. In addition to typical facial features, carriers of the G-syndrome have been noted to have dysphagia and respiratory difficulties, stridor, and hoarse voice. Scoliosis and ophthalmological disorders were not previously noted in carriers of this condition.
