904. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase <1974 to 1979>
AN  - 7112933
T1  - Luteinizing hormone releasing hormone for induction of follicular maturation and ovulation in women, BASIC APPLICATIONS AND CLINICAL USES OF HYPOTHALAMIC HORMONES
A1  - Nillius S.J.
A1  - Wide L. 
Y1  - 1976//
N2  - This study shows that LRH alone can induce both follicular maturation and ovulation in amenorrheic women who are without signs of endogenous ovarian activity before treatment. Thus, it seems possible to replace human gonadotrophins with LRH for induction of ovulation, at least in some amenorrheic women. LRH may be preferable to human gonadotrophins since there will be no need to monitor the endocrine status to avoid ovarian hyperstimulation, a serious complication with the latter therapy. The dose of HMG has to be adjusted according to the ovarian response. The interrelationship between the pituitary and the ovaries in LRH treated patients may be regarded as an internal control mechanism. LRH induces synthesis and release of FSH and LH from the pituitary. The gonadotrophins stimulate the ovaries to secrete estradiol and progesterone which then feed back on the pituitary to modify pituitary responsiveness to LRH. This feedback system between the ovarian steroids and the pituitary may, hopefully, automatically prevent excessive FSH stimulation of the ovaries during prolonged treatment with high doses of LRH. However, more clinical studies are required before the exact status of LRH in anovulatory infertility therapy can be defined. The studies on anorexia nervosa prove that LRH can be used alone or in combination with HCG to induce follicular growth, maturation, ovulation and pregnancy. It remains to be seen whether LRH treatment will be as effective in other amenorrheic women.
